P\" />\n}}\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Esther Joy King (R)\n| width= 68em\n| list =\n;Federal officials\n*[[Tom Cotton]], U.S. Senator (R-AR)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TomCottonAR/status/1229780909441855489|title=.@Esther4congress is the best choice for Illinois 17th district. Esther is a captain in the Army Reserves, she\u2019s a strong conservative, and she\u2019s taking on the head of the DCCC. This is a D+3 district and with our support, Esther can win.|first=Tom|last=Cotton|date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n;Organizations\n*[[Susan B. Anthony List]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sba-list.org/candidate/esther-joy-king|title=Esther Joy King|accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===General election===\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois's 17th congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Cheri Bustos]] (incumbent)\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \t\n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Esther Joy King\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \t\n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes =\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 18==\n{{see also|Illinois's 18th congressional district}}\nThe 18th district covers rural [[Central Illinois|west-central Illinois]], including [[Jacksonville, Illinois|Jacksonville]], [[Quincy, Illinois|Quincy]] and parts of [[Bloomington, Illinois|Bloomington]], [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]], and [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]]. The incumbent is Republican [[Darin LaHood]], who was re-elected with 67.2% of the vote in 2018.<ref name=\"HPVT\" />\n\n===Republican primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Nominee=====\n*[[Darin LaHood]], incumbent U.S. Representative<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vlahos |first1=Nick |title=U.S. Rep. Darin LaHood says he's running for re-election in 2020 |url=https://www.sj-r.com/news/20190814/us-rep-darin-lahood-says-hes-running-for-re-election-in-2020 |website=The State Journal-Register |date=August 14, 2019 |accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Primary results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Darin LaHood]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\n=====Withdrawn=====\n* Mark Haasis, former national organizer for [[United Automobile Workers]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schoenburg |first1=Bernard |title=Democrat announces bid against Darin LaHood |url=https://www.pjstar.com/news/20191023/democrat-announces-bid-against-darin-lahood |date=October 23, 2019 |accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===General election===\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois's 18th congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Darin LaHood]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n;Find your district/elected officials\n* [https://elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/DistrictLocator/AddressFinder.aspx Find your district/elected officials] \n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n;Official campaign websites for 1st district candidates\n* [https://philaniseforcongress.com/ Philanise White (R) for Congress]\n\n;Official campaign websites for 2nd district candidates\n* [http://www.robinkellyforcongress.org/ Robin Kelly (D) for Congress]\n* [https://www.rabornforcongress.com/ Theresa Raborn (R) for Congress]\n\n;Official campaign websites for 3rd district candidates\n* [https://mikefricilone.com/ M