ction box begin no change\n| title = Illinois's 13th congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Rodney Davis (politician)|Rodney Davis]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \t\n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Betsy Dirksen Londrigan\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \t\n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 14==\n{{see also|Illinois's 14th congressional district}}\nThe 14th district encompasses the western [[Chicago]] exurbs, including all or parts of [[Batavia, Illinois|Batavia]], [[Campton Hills, Illinois|Campton Hills]], [[Crystal Lake, Illinois|Crystal Lake]], [[Geneva, Illinois|Geneva]], [[Huntley, Illinois|Huntley]], [[McHenry, Illinois|McHenry]], [[Naperville, Illinois|Naperville]], [[Saint Charles, Illinois|St. Charles]], [[North Aurora, Illinois|North Aurora]], [[Oswego, Illinois|Oswego]], [[Plainfield, Illinois|Plainfield]], [[Plano, Illinois|Plano]], [[Sycamore, Illinois|Sycamore]], [[Warrenville, Illinois|Warrenville]], [[Wauconda, Illinois|Wauconda]], [[Woodstock, Illinois|Woodstock]], and [[Yorkville, Illinois|Yorkville]]. The incumbent is Democrat [[Lauren Underwood]], who flipped the district and was elected with 52.5% of the vote in 2018.<ref name=\"HPVT\" />\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Nominee=====\n*[[Lauren Underwood]], incumbent U.S. Representative<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=U.S. Rep. Lauren Underwood makes it official: She'll run for a second term|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/politics/ct-lauren-underwood-announces-reelection-bid-20190629-jnp4xr7j3ree5k7hxxl55funay-story.html|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 29, 2019|accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=====Endorsements=====\n{{endorsements box\n|title = Lauren Underwood\n| width= 68em\n|li