{"title_page": "James Molyneaux, Baron Molyneaux of Killead", "text_new": "{{Other people|James Molyneux}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =[[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Molyneaux of Killead\n|honorific-suffix = [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire|KBE]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n|image            = The Lord Molyneaux of Killead KBE, PC.gif\n|image_size       =\n\n|office          = [[Leaders of the Ulster Unionist Party|Leader of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n|term_start      = 7 September 1979\n|term_end        = 8 September 1995\n|predecessor     = [[Harry West]]\n|successor       = [[David Trimble, Baron Trimble|David Trimble]]\n|office2          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Lagan Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Lagan Valley]]\n|term_start2      = 9 June 1983\n|term_end2        = 1 May 1997\n|predecessor2     = ''Constituency created''\n|successor2       = [[Jeffrey Donaldson]]\n|office3          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br /> for [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]]\n|term_start3     = 18 June 1970\n|term_end3        = 9 June 1983\n|predecessor3     = [[Knox Cunningham]]\n|successor3       = [[Clifford Forsythe]]\n|office1          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br /><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start1      = 10 June 1997\n|term_end1         = 9 March 2015<br /><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|birth_name=James Henry Molyneaux\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1920|08|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Killead]], Ireland\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|2015|03|09|1920|08|27|df=y}}\n|death_place      = [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]], Northern Ireland\n|nationality      = [[Northern Irish]]\n|residence        = Killead, [[County Antrim]]\n|party            = [[Ulster Unionist Party]] \n|alma_mater       = \n| allegiance    = {{UK}}\n| branch        = [[File:Royal Airforce Badge.png|23px]] [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears  = 1941\u20131946\n| rank          = [[Flying Officer]]\n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = [[World War Two]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        =\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n'''James Henry Molyneaux, Baron Molyneaux of Killead''', [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] (27 August 1920 \u2013 9 March 2015<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bergenbelsen.co.uk/pages/Database/ReliefStaff.asp?HeroesID=179 | title=(later Lord) James Henry Molyneaux K.B.E. | publisher=Bergenbelsen.co.uk | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>), often known as '''Jim Molyneaux''', was a [[Northern Irish]] [[Unionists (Ireland)|unionist]] politician, and leader of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] from 1979 to 1995. He was a leading member and sometime Vice-President of the [[Conservative Monday Club]]. An [[Orange Institution|Orangeman]],<ref name=kaufmann>http://www.sneps.net/OO/photos.htm Eric Kaufmann's Orange Order Page \u2013 Photos, retrieved 19 November 2007.</ref> he was also Sovereign Grand Master of the [[Royal Black Institution]] from 1971 to 1995.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Killead]], [[County Antrim]] to William Molyneaux and Sarah Gilmore,<ref>Burke's Peerage 2003, Volume 2, p.2730</ref> Molyneaux was educated at nearby Aldergrove School. Although he was raised an Anglican, as a child he briefly attended a local Catholic primary school.<ref name=belfast_telegraph /> When a Catholic church near his home was burnt down by [[Ulster loyalist]] arsonists in the late 1990s, Molyneaux helped to raise funds for its rebuilding.<ref name=belfast_telegraph>{{cite news | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/Obituaries/james-molyneaux-political-fighter-and-committed-churchman-who-was-a-stabilising-force-for-the-ulster-unionists-31053682.html | title=James Molyneaux: Political fighter and committed churchman who was a stabilising force for the Ulster Unionists | newspaper=Belfast Telegraph | accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nIn [[World War II]] Molyneaux served in the [[Royal Air Force]] between 1941 and 1946. He participated in the liberation of the [[Belsen]] concentration camp, and occasionally gave interviews about what he saw there. On 1 April 1947, he was promoted to [[flying officer]].<ref name=\"LG 12 December 1947\">{{London Gazette |issue=38147 |date=12 December 1947 |pages=5923\u20135932  |supp=y }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UuHlBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA212| title=Handbuch des britischen Adels 2015| isbn=9783734743795| last1=West| first1=Thomas Baron de| date=2014-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDuring the 1960s and 1970s, Molyneaux served on [[Antrim County Council]], as well as a number of committees concerning local healthcare, and in 1970 was elected UUP [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]]. In October 1974, Molyneaux became leader of the Ulster Unionists in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]. Between 1982 and 1986 he sat as a UUP member for South Antrim in the failed [[1982 Northern Ireland Assembly]]. Molyneaux was admitted to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1982. Following boundary changes that divided South Antrim, Molyneaux became member for the new seat of [[Lagan Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Lagan Valley]] in 1983. In 1985, Molyneaux resigned his seat, along with his unionist colleagues in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], in protest at the [[Anglo-Irish Agreement]]. He was re-elected in the subsequent [[by-election]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld/hl1/114.htm | title=House of Lords List of Members | publisher=Publications.parliament.uk | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMolyneaux was generally regarded as a member of the integrationist tendency within the UUP (favouring direct rule from Westminster with some extension of local government powers, as opposed to the devolutionist preference for a revived Northern Ireland parliament or assembly).<ref>Patterson, H. (2012) 'Unionism After Good Friday and St Andrews' in ''The Political Quarterly, Vol. 83, No.2'' (London:Wiley-Blackwell)</ref>  This preference was widely attributed to the influence of [[Enoch Powell]]. Critics within Molyneaux's party saw Molyneux as a do-nothing leader, unduly deferential towards the Conservative Party (leading him to be taken by surprise by the Anglo-Irish Agreement and overshadowed by [[Ian Paisley]]).  Molyneaux's defenders would probably argue that his primary concern was party unity, that the UUP was so divided that only a minimalist policy could hold it together.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-of-lord-molyneaux-by-alex-kane-1-6622320 | title=Obituary of Lord Molyneaux by Alex Kane | publisher=NewsLetter | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1980s, Molyneaux was an active member of the [[Conservative Monday Club]]. Molyneaux was co-opted onto the Club's Executive Council on 23 June 1983.<ref>''Monday News'' October 1983, p.3.</ref> He later became a Vice-President of the Club.  In the October 1985 Conservative Party Conference issue of the Club's tabloid newspaper, ''Right Ahead'', he contributed a lengthy article entitled \"Northern Ireland \u2013 Ulster belongs to Britain NOT to the Irish Republic\". Molyneaux had been present at the crucial Executive Council meeting of 19 December 1990 which accepted, by 11 votes to 3, the decision to stop employing salaried staff at the Club because of its financial deficit.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://research.un.org/en/docs/ga/quick/regular/45 | title=Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld Library Research | publisher=UN EM | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} Molyneaux subsequently left the Monday Club in February 1991.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn 1994, the [[Provisional IRA]] called a ceasefire, which Molyneaux described as \"the most destabilising event since partition\"<ref>http://republican-news.org/current/news/2015/03/death_of_no-frills_unionist_pa.html</ref> and \"the worst thing that has ever happened to us\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.derryjournal.com/news/ira-ceasefire-anniversary-how-the-events-unfolded-20-years-ago-1-6270464 | title=IRA ceasefire anniversary: How the events unfolded 20 years ago}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995 Molyneaux was [[March 1995 Ulster Unionist Party leadership election|challenged for the leadership of the UUP]] by a 21-year-old student and, although winning easily, saw a strong protest vote against Molyneaux's leadership registered. Following the UUP's poor showing in the [[1995 North Down by-election]], Molyneaux yielded to renewed pressure to retire as leader. On retiring as UUP leader, Molyneaux was [[knight]]ed as a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) in 1996.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54255 |date=30 December 1995 |page=8 |supp=y}}</ref> The following year, after standing down as an MP at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], Molyneaux was created a [[life peer]] on 10 June 1997 as '''Baron Molyneaux of Killead''', of [[Killead]] in the [[County of Antrim]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54811 |date=19 June 1997 |page=7123}}</ref>\n\nOn several occasions in his retirement, Molyneaux was publicly critical of his successor, [[David Trimble]]. He fiercely opposed the [[Belfast Agreement|Good Friday Agreement]], and in 2003 supported three Ulster Unionist MPs ([[David Burnside]], [[Jeffrey Donaldson]] and [[Martin Smyth]]) when they resigned the party whip in protest against Trimble's leadership and the party's support for the Agreement. In the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Molyneaux caused a storm when he and Smyth endorsed the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] candidate [[Jimmy Spratt (politician)|Jimmy Spratt]] over the UUP candidate [[Michael McGimpsey]] in Smyth's former constituency of [[South Belfast (UK Parliament constituency)|South Belfast]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-herald/20150310/282252368998645/TextView | title=PressReader | publisher=The Herald | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Molyneaux also endorsed Donaldson, his own successor as MP for Lagan Valley, even after Donaldson had defected to the DUP, as well as anti-Trimble UUP candidates such as Burnside. In the election, Donaldson held Lagan Valley by a large majority, while Spratt outpolled McGimpsey (although losing to the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party|SDLP]] candidate [[Alasdair McDonnell]] on a split vote); many claimed that Molyneaux and Smyth's endorsements had contributed to the UUP's disastrous showing. However, Burnside lost his seat.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://aims.niassembly.gov.uk/officialreport/report.aspx?&eveDate=2015/03/09&docID=226892 | title=Official Report: Monday 09 March 2015 | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMolyneaux died at the age of 94 in [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]], Northern Ireland on 9 March 2015, [[Commonwealth Day]].<ref name=\"BBC 31793756\">{{cite news|title=James Molyneaux: Former UUP leader dies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-31793756|accessdate=9 March 2015|agency=BBC Online|publisher=BBC|date=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Belfast Telegraph 31051422\">{{cite news|title=James Molyneaux: Former UUP leader dies age 94|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/james-molyneaux-former-uup-leader-dies-age-94-31051422.html|accessdate=9 March 2015|newspaper=Belfast Telegraph|date=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/ni/?id=2015-03-09.1.1 | title=TheyWorkForYou | accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 right-wing activist Christopher Luke claimed that he had had a long-term relationship with Molyneaux until the latter's death.<ref>[http://www.irishnews.com/news/2016/03/11/news/former-uup-leader-lord-molyneaux-s-close-companion-tells-of-30-year-relationship-446435/ Former UUP leader James Molyneaux's \u2018close companion' tells of 30-year relationship]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-35782185 Lord Molyneaux's 'close companion' tells of 'very loving relationship']</ref> Molyneaux's relatives questioned the veracity of Luke's claims.<ref>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/jim-molyneaux-family-dismayed-at-close-relationship-claims-made-by-christopher-luke-34533381.html Jim Molyneaux family dismayed at 'close relationship' claims made by Christopher Luke]</ref> Luke died at the age of 50 in December 2017.<ref>[https://www.irishnews.com/news/2017/12/12/news/lord-molyneaux-close-companion-christopher-luke-dies-in-england-1208262/ Lord Molyneaux `close companion' Christopher Luke dies in England]</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Gyronny of eight Or and Azure a cross moline between four alder leaves slipped inwards all counterchanged.\n|crest = A wolf statant Or holding in the dexter forepaw a flax flower Azure slipped and leaved Or.\n|supporters = On either side a heraldic tyger reguardant Argent gorged with a plain collar attached thereto a chain reflexed over the back Or.\n|motto = In Hoc Signo Vinces <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Northern Ireland Members of the House of Lords]]\n* [[List of Northern Ireland members of the Privy Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-molyneaux | James Molyneaux }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]]\n  | years  = 1970\u20131983\n  | before = Sir [[Knox Cunningham]]\n  | after  = [[Clifford Forsythe]]\n}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Lagan Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Lagan Valley]]\n  | years  = 1983\u20131997\n}}\n{{s-aft  | after  = [[Jeffrey Donaldson]] }}\n\n{{s-par|ni/ass82}}\n{{s-new | Assembly }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of the Parliamentary Assembly|MPA]] for [[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]]\n  | years = 1982\u20131986\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Assembly abolished }}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Ulster Unionist Party|Leader of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n  | years  = 1979\u20131995\n  | before = [[Harry West]]\n  | after  = [[David Trimble]]\n}}\n{{s-npo}}\n{{succession box | title=Sovereign Grand Master of the [[Royal Black Preceptory]] | before=[[Norman Stronge|Sir Norman Stronge]] | after=[[William Logan (Orangeman)|William Logan]] | years=1971\u20131995}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UUP Leaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molyneaux of Killead, James Molyneaux, Baron}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of Armagh County Council]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers|Molyneaux of Killead]] <!-- title only -->\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Antrim constituencies (since 1922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Lagan Valley]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MPAs 1982\u20131986]]\n[[Category:People from County Antrim]]\n[[Category:People of The Troubles (Northern Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party life peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|James Molyneux}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =[[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Molyneaux of Killead\n|honorific-suffix = [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire|KBE]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n|image            = The Lord Molyneaux of Killead KBE, PC.gif\n|image_size       =\n\n|office          = [[Leaders of the Ulster Unionist Party|Leader of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n|term_start      = 7 September 1979\n|term_end        = 8 September 1995\n|predecessor     = [[Harry West]]\n|successor       = [[David Trimble, Baron Trimble|David Trimble]]\n|office2          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Lagan Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Lagan Valley]]\n|term_start2      = 9 June 1983\n|term_end2        = 1 May 1997\n|predecessor2     = ''Constituency created''\n|successor2       = [[Jeffrey Donaldson]]\n|office3          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br /> for [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]]\n|term_start3     = 18 June 1970\n|term_end3        = 9 June 1983\n|predecessor3     = [[Knox Cunningham]]\n|successor3       = [[Clifford Forsythe]]\n|office1          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br /><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start1      = 10 June 1997\n|term_end1         = 9 March 2015<br /><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|birth_name=James Henry Molyneaux\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1920|08|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Killead]], Ireland\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|2015|03|09|1920|08|27|df=y}}\n|death_place      = [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]], Northern Ireland\n|nationality      = [[Northern Irish]]\n|residence        = Killead, [[County Antrim]]\n|party            = [[Ulster Unionist Party]] \n|alma_mater       = \n| allegiance    = {{UK}}\n| branch        = [[File:Royal Airforce Badge.png|23px]] [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears  = 1941\u20131946\n| rank          = [[Flying Officer]]\n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = [[World War Two]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        =\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n'''James Henry Molyneaux, Baron Molyneaux of Killead''', [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] (27 August 1920 \u2013 9 March 2015<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bergenbelsen.co.uk/pages/Database/ReliefStaff.asp?HeroesID=179 | title=(later Lord) James Henry Molyneaux K.B.E. | publisher=Bergenbelsen.co.uk | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>), often known as '''Jim Molyneaux''', was a [[Northern Irish]] [[Unionists (Ireland)|unionist]] politician, and leader of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] from 1979 to 1995. He was a leading member and sometime Vice-President of the [[Conservative Monday Club]]. An [[Orange Institution|Orangeman]],<ref name=kaufmann>http://www.sneps.net/OO/photos.htm Eric Kaufmann's Orange Order Page \u2013 Photos, retrieved 19 November 2007.</ref> he was also Sovereign Grand Master of the [[Royal Black Institution]] from 1971 to 1995.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Killead]], [[County Antrim]] to William Molyneaux and Sarah Gilmore,<ref>Burke's Peerage 2003, Volume 2, p.2730</ref> Molyneaux was educated at nearby Aldergrove School. Although he was raised an Anglican, as a child he briefly attended a local Catholic primary school.<ref name=belfast_telegraph /> When a Catholic church near his home was burnt down by [[Ulster loyalist]] arsonists in the late 1990s, Molyneaux helped to raise funds for its rebuilding.<ref name=belfast_telegraph>{{cite news | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/Obituaries/james-molyneaux-political-fighter-and-committed-churchman-who-was-a-stabilising-force-for-the-ulster-unionists-31053682.html | title=James Molyneaux: Political fighter and committed churchman who was a stabilising force for the Ulster Unionists | newspaper=Belfast Telegraph | accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\nIn [[World War II]] Molyneaux served in the [[Royal Air Force]] between 1941 and 1946. He participated in the liberation of the [[Belsen]] concentration camp, and occasionally gave interviews about what he saw there. On 1 April 1947, he was promoted to [[flying officer]].<ref name=\"LG 12 December 1947\">{{London Gazette |issue=38147 |date=12 December 1947 |pages=5923\u20135932  |supp=y }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UuHlBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA212| title=Handbuch des britischen Adels 2015| isbn=9783734743795| last1=West| first1=Thomas Baron de| date=2014-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDuring the 1960s and 1970s, Molyneaux served on [[Antrim County Council]], as well as a number of committees concerning local healthcare, and in 1970 was elected UUP [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]]. In October 1974, Molyneaux became leader of the Ulster Unionists in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]. Between 1982 and 1986 he sat as a UUP member for South Antrim in the failed [[1982 Northern Ireland Assembly]]. Molyneaux was admitted to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1982. Following boundary changes that divided South Antrim, Molyneaux became member for the new seat of [[Lagan Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Lagan Valley]] in 1983. In 1985, Molyneaux resigned his seat, along with his unionist colleagues in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], in protest at the [[Anglo-Irish Agreement]]. He was re-elected in the subsequent [[by-election]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld/hl1/114.htm | title=House of Lords List of Members | publisher=Publications.parliament.uk | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMolyneaux was generally regarded as a member of the integrationist tendency within the UUP (favouring direct rule from Westminster with some extension of local government powers, as opposed to the devolutionist preference for a revived Northern Ireland parliament or assembly).<ref>Patterson, H. (2012) 'Unionism After Good Friday and St Andrews' in ''The Political Quarterly, Vol. 83, No.2'' (London:Wiley-Blackwell)</ref>  This preference was widely attributed to the influence of [[Enoch Powell]]. Critics within Molyneaux's party saw Molyneux as a do-nothing leader, unduly deferential towards the Conservative Party (leading him to be taken by surprise by the Anglo-Irish Agreement and overshadowed by [[Ian Paisley]]).  Molyneaux's defenders would probably argue that his primary concern was party unity, that the UUP was so divided that only a minimalist policy could hold it together.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-of-lord-molyneaux-by-alex-kane-1-6622320 | title=Obituary of Lord Molyneaux by Alex Kane | publisher=NewsLetter | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1980s, Molyneaux was an active member of the [[Conservative Monday Club]]. Molyneaux was co-opted onto the Club's Executive Council on 23 June 1983.<ref>''Monday News'' October 1983, p.3.</ref> He later became a Vice-President of the Club.  In the October 1985 Conservative Party Conference issue of the Club\u2019s tabloid newspaper, ''Right Ahead'', he contributed a lengthy article entitled \"Northern Ireland \u2013 Ulster belongs to Britain NOT to the Irish Republic\". Molyneaux had been present at the crucial Executive Council meeting of 19 December 1990 which accepted, by 11 votes to 3, the decision to stop employing salaried staff at the Club because of its financial deficit.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://research.un.org/en/docs/ga/quick/regular/45 | title=Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld Library Research | publisher=UN EM | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} Molyneaux subsequently left the Monday Club in February 1991.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn 1994, the [[Provisional IRA]] called a ceasefire, which Molyneaux described as \"the most destabilising event since partition\"<ref>http://republican-news.org/current/news/2015/03/death_of_no-frills_unionist_pa.html</ref> and \"the worst thing that has ever happened to us\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.derryjournal.com/news/ira-ceasefire-anniversary-how-the-events-unfolded-20-years-ago-1-6270464 | title=IRA ceasefire anniversary: How the events unfolded 20 years ago}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995 Molyneaux was [[March 1995 Ulster Unionist Party leadership election|challenged for the leadership of the UUP]] by a 21-year-old student and, although winning easily, saw a strong protest vote against Molyneaux's leadership registered. Following the UUP's poor showing in the [[1995 North Down by-election]], Molyneaux yielded to renewed pressure to retire as leader. On retiring as UUP leader, Molyneaux was [[knight]]ed as a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) in 1996.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54255 |date=30 December 1995 |page=8 |supp=y}}</ref> The following year, after standing down as an MP at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], Molyneaux was created a [[life peer]] on 10 June 1997 as '''Baron Molyneaux of Killead''', of [[Killead]] in the [[County of Antrim]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54811 |date=19 June 1997 |page=7123}}</ref>\n\nOn several occasions in his retirement, Molyneaux was publicly critical of his successor, [[David Trimble]]. He fiercely opposed the [[Belfast Agreement|Good Friday Agreement]], and in 2003 supported three Ulster Unionist MPs ([[David Burnside]], [[Jeffrey Donaldson]] and [[Martin Smyth]]) when they resigned the party whip in protest against Trimble's leadership and the party's support for the Agreement. In the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Molyneaux caused a storm when he and Smyth endorsed the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] candidate [[Jimmy Spratt (politician)|Jimmy Spratt]] over the UUP candidate [[Michael McGimpsey]] in Smyth's former constituency of [[South Belfast (UK Parliament constituency)|South Belfast]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-herald/20150310/282252368998645/TextView | title=PressReader | publisher=The Herald | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Molyneaux also endorsed Donaldson, his own successor as MP for Lagan Valley, even after Donaldson had defected to the DUP, as well as anti-Trimble UUP candidates such as Burnside. In the election, Donaldson held Lagan Valley by a large majority, while Spratt outpolled McGimpsey (although losing to the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party|SDLP]] candidate [[Alasdair McDonnell]] on a split vote); many claimed that Molyneaux and Smyth's endorsements had contributed to the UUP's disastrous showing. However, Burnside lost his seat.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://aims.niassembly.gov.uk/officialreport/report.aspx?&eveDate=2015/03/09&docID=226892 | title=Official Report: Monday 09 March 2015 | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMolyneaux died at the age of 94 in [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]], Northern Ireland on 9 March 2015, [[Commonwealth Day]].<ref name=\"BBC 31793756\">{{cite news|title=James Molyneaux: Former UUP leader dies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-31793756|accessdate=9 March 2015|agency=BBC Online|publisher=BBC|date=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Belfast Telegraph 31051422\">{{cite news|title=James Molyneaux: Former UUP leader dies age 94|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/james-molyneaux-former-uup-leader-dies-age-94-31051422.html|accessdate=9 March 2015|newspaper=Belfast Telegraph|date=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/ni/?id=2015-03-09.1.1 | title=TheyWorkForYou | accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 right-wing activist Christopher Luke claimed that he had had a long-term relationship with Molyneaux until the latter's death.<ref>[http://www.irishnews.com/news/2016/03/11/news/former-uup-leader-lord-molyneaux-s-close-companion-tells-of-30-year-relationship-446435/ Former UUP leader James Molyneaux's \u2018close companion' tells of 30-year relationship]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-35782185 Lord Molyneaux's 'close companion' tells of 'very loving relationship']</ref> Molyneaux's relatives questioned the veracity of Luke's claims.<ref>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/jim-molyneaux-family-dismayed-at-close-relationship-claims-made-by-christopher-luke-34533381.html Jim Molyneaux family dismayed at 'close relationship' claims made by Christopher Luke]</ref> Luke died at the age of 50 in December 2017.<ref>[https://www.irishnews.com/news/2017/12/12/news/lord-molyneaux-close-companion-christopher-luke-dies-in-england-1208262/ Lord Molyneaux `close companion' Christopher Luke dies in England]</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Gyronny of eight Or and Azure a cross moline between four alder leaves slipped inwards all counterchanged.\n|crest = A wolf statant Or holding in the dexter forepaw a flax flower Azure slipped and leaved Or.\n|supporters = On either side a heraldic tyger reguardant Argent gorged with a plain collar attached thereto a chain reflexed over the back Or.\n|motto = In Hoc Signo Vinces <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Northern Ireland Members of the House of Lords]]\n* [[List of Northern Ireland members of the Privy Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-molyneaux | James Molyneaux }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]]\n  | years  = 1970\u20131983\n  | before = Sir [[Knox Cunningham]]\n  | after  = [[Clifford Forsythe]]\n}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Lagan Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Lagan Valley]]\n  | years  = 1983\u20131997\n}}\n{{s-aft  | after  = [[Jeffrey Donaldson]] }}\n\n{{s-par|ni/ass82}}\n{{s-new | Assembly }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of the Parliamentary Assembly|MPA]] for [[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]]\n  | years = 1982\u20131986\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Assembly abolished }}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Ulster Unionist Party|Leader of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n  | years  = 1979\u20131995\n  | before = [[Harry West]]\n  | after  = [[David Trimble]]\n}}\n{{s-npo}}\n{{succession box | title=Sovereign Grand Master of the [[Royal Black Preceptory]] | before=[[Norman Stronge|Sir Norman Stronge]] | after=[[William Logan (Orangeman)|William Logan]] | years=1971\u20131995}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UUP Leaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molyneaux of Killead, James Molyneaux, Baron}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of Armagh County Council]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers|Molyneaux of Killead]] <!-- title only -->\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Antrim constituencies (since 1922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Lagan Valley]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MPAs 1982\u20131986]]\n[[Category:People from County Antrim]]\n[[Category:People of The Troubles (Northern Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party life peers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Molyneaux,_Baron_Molyneaux_of_Killead"}
{"title_page": "Colin Mitchell", "text_new": "{{for|the cricketer|Colin Mitchell (cricketer)}}\n{{distinguish|Collin Mitchell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n<!--as Colin Mitchell redirects here-->\n{{Infobox military person \n|name=Colin Campbell Mitchell\n|birth_date= 17 November 1925\n|death_date= 20 July 1996 (aged 70)\n|birth_place= [[Croydon]], [[Surrey]], England\n|death_place= [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|placeofburial= \n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Colin Campbell Mitchell.jpg\n|caption=Colin Mitchell c.1967 \n|nickname=Mad Mitch\n|allegiance={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch={{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears=1943\u20131968\n|rank=[[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|commands= 1st Battalion, [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]]\n|battles=[[World War II]]<br/>[[Palestine Emergency]]<br/>[[Korean War]]<br>[[Cyprus Emergency]]<br/>[[Indonesia\u2013Malaysia confrontation]]<br/>[[Aden Emergency]]\n|laterwork=[[Member of Parliament]]<br/>Founder of the [[Halo Trust]]}}\n\n'''Colin Campbell Mitchell''' (17 November 1925 \u2013 20 July 1996) was a [[British Army]] soldier and politician. He became a public figure in 1967 as the commanding officer of the 1st Battalion of the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]]. Forces under his command reoccupied the Crater district of Aden which had been taken over by local police mutineers in what became known as [[Battle of the Crater (Aden)|\"the last battle of the British empire\"]]. The reoccupation and subsequent control of the Crater were controversial and Mitchell resigned his army commission in 1968. Subsequently, he became a Conservative Member of Parliament and served one term from 1970 to February 1974. After participation in a failed business venture he subsequently worked as a security and military consultant. In 1989 Mitchell took a leading role in the [[Halo Trust]], a not-for-profit organisation undertaking mine clearance in former war zones.\n\n==Early life==\nMitchell's father (also called Colin) came from an Argyllshire fishing family. Mitchell (Snr) worked in a solicitor's office and for the [[David MacBrayne Ltd|MacBrayne ferry company]] before serving in the 10th Battalion Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders in [[World War I]]. Mitchell (Snr) achieved the rank of captain (commissioned \u2018in the field\u2019) and was awarded the [[Military Cross]] at the [[Second Battle of Ypres]], but when the young Colin asked him how he would only say, 'Oh, shooting rabbits'. He was badly gassed in 1918. After the war, he worked in the City of London and married a [[Glaswegian]] woman (n\u00e9e Gilmour) whose father worked as a manager for the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] Railway company. The couple took up residence in the South London suburb of [[Purley, London|Purley]] where they had two children \u2013 Colin and Henrietta. The family lived in a modest semi-detached house and Colin would attend services at the local [[Presbyterian]] Church wearing a [[kilt]].<ref>''[[The Independent]]'', obituary, early paragraphs on family history in 'free to view' section :[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19960724/ai_n14059912/pg_1 Lt-Col Colin Mitchell], by [[Tam Dalyell]] - 24 July 1996</ref> Mitchell received his formal education at the [[Whitgift School|Whitgift Grammar School]] in [[Croydon]].\n\n==Military career==\nIn 1940, at age 15, Mitchell enlisted in the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]], and may have been the youngest Home Guard soldier. In May 1943 he joined the [[British Army]], enlisting as a private in the [[Royal West Kent Regiment]]. He soon became a Lance-Corporal and instructed newcomers in physical training. One of his fellow instructors was [[Stan Cullis]] who had been the captain of the [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]] [[1939 FA Cup Final|cup side at Wembley in 1939]] and was the captain of [[England national football team|England]] at the time. Mitchell was commissioned into the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]] in 1944.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36843|supp=y|page=5788|date=15 December 1944}}</ref> He fought in the final battles of the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian campaign]], and was lightly wounded in the advance on [[Ferrara]]. Despite this, his wartime experience inclined him to take up a military career.<ref>''[[The Independent]]'', obituary :[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary--ltcol-colin-mitchell-1330247.html Lt-Col Colin Mitchell], by [[Tam Dalyell]] - 24 July 1996</ref>  He was appointed to a regular commission on 21 December 1946.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37823|supp=y|page=6169|date=17 December 1946}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the war, he saw action against Jewish guerrillas during the [[Jewish insurgency in Palestine|Palestine Emergency]]. While in Palestine, he participated in operations to arrest Jewish militants. During [[Operation Agatha]], which saw most of the Jewish political leadership in Palestine detained, Mitchell's mission was to arrest [[Moshe Sharett|Moshe Shertok]] (a future [[Prime Minister of Israel]]). Initially, his unit raided the wrong house. However, they were later able to find and arrest him. In July 1946, he witnessed the [[King David Hotel bombing]]: he and his company commander were within 300 feet of the building when the bombing occurred. While on a personal reconnaissance mission, he was shot and wounded by one of his own Bren gunners, who mistook him for a guerrilla. After recovering from his injuries, he was transferred from his regiment to become [[aide-de-camp]] to General [[Gordon Holmes MacMillan|Gordon MacMillan]], the commander of British forces in Palestine and Transjordan. He spent a total of three years in Palestine. While there, he made friends among both the Arabs and Jews, including [[Moshe Dayan]], a future Israeli general who would become one of Mitchell's heroes, as well as Moshe Shertok, who developed a cordial relationship with Mitchell after his arrest and corresponded with him for years afterward, when he became a senior Israeli government official.<ref>http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/nov/17/northern-ireland-compton-committees</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/army-obituaries/5796166/Lt-Col-C-C-Mad-Mitch-Mitchell.html Lt-Col C C 'Mad Mitch' Mitchell]</ref>\n\nIn 1950, with the outbreak of the [[Korean War]], he was allowed to rejoin his regiment so he could deploy to Korea. He participated in the initial advance into [[North Korea]], seeing close-quarters combat along the way. His regiment ultimately reached [[Taechon]], near the Chinese border on the [[Yalu River]]. When the Chinese Army intervened and crossed the Yalu River in overwhelming numbers, the regiment was forced to take part in the retreat of UN forces, and later helped hold the line against Communist forces when UN forces consolidated. The regiment held a position known as \"Frostbite Ridge\", where they had to endure freezing conditions. They held the area through the winter until the thaw, and in 1951, they began to advance. However, shortly afterward, they were relieved and withdrawn.<ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\"/>\n\nFollowing his service in Korea, Mitchell was posted in Britain, but in late 1957, he returned to the Argylls as a company commander with the 1st Battalion, and was posted to [[Cyprus]]. At the time, the [[Cyprus Emergency]] was in full swing. Mitchell was placed in charge of the coastal towns of [[Paphos]] and Ktima, where his men engaged in counter-insurgency operations against [[EOKA]] guerrillas. They faced both conventional EOKA raids and forest fires deliberately lit by EOKA fighters and local villagers who were motivated by the money they would receive to fight them.<ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\"/><ref>Edwards, Aaron: ''Mad Mitch's Tribal Law: Aden and the End of Empire''</ref>\n\nMitchell was subsequently posted to the [[British Army of the Rhine]] with the rest of the regiment, and then joined the [[King's African Rifles]], and was posted to [[East Africa]]. Soon afterward, he saw action in [[Zanzibar]] with the KAR in breaking up disturbances between the island's Arab and African populations, which had begun during a general election and had descended into widespread rioting and clashes. He also participated in operations on the [[Northern Frontier District]]. At the time, Somali guerrillas were launching raids as part of a campaign to unite the region with Somalia, and the frontiers with other neighbouring states were also volatile. In one incident, Mitchell was searching for Somali guerrillas in a low-flying helicopter, and an elephant attempted to attack the helicopter, nearly clipping it with its tusks. It has been claimed that while with the KAR Mitchell was instrumental in obtaining a commission for [[Idi Amin]], who later became President of [[Uganda]]. Mitchell's familiarity with the Scottish [[Scottish clan|clan system]] made him more comfortable with African tribal issues than was the case with his English contemporaries. Impressed by Mitchell and other Scottish officers, Amin would later adopt the title [[The Last King of Scotland|''King of Scotland'']].<ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\"/><ref>''[[The New York Times]]'':[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/27/world/colin-mitchell-is-dead-at-70-british-hero-in-aden-battles.html Mitchell's 1996 obituary]</ref>\n\nFollowing his service in Kenya, Mitchell rejoined the Argylls, which was sent to [[Borneo]] to participate in the [[Indonesian-Malaysian Confrontation]]. Mitchell participated in a series of clashes with Indonesian forces. After six months of jungle warfare, the regiment was sent back to [[Singapore]] to recuperate. Mitchell was posted back to the UK as a staff officer. Throughout all this time Mitchell was making a reputation as a bold and efficient officer, passing out top of [[Staff College, Camberley|Staff College]] and serving as GSO1 on the staff of [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence staff]], [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Mountbatten]]. Mitchell was promoted [[First Lieutenant|lieutenant]] in 1947,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38240|page=1926|date=16 March 1948}}</ref> [[captain (OF-2)|captain]] in 1952,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39696|supp=y|page=6068|date=14 November 1952}}</ref> [[major (United Kingdom)|major]] in 1959,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41868|supp=y|page=7246|date=13 November 1959}}</ref> and his success in a wide range of appointments won him [[brevet rank]] as a lieutenant-colonel in 1964.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=43371|supp=y|page=5715|date=30 June 1964}}</ref>\n\nMitchell was promoted to substantive lieutenant-colonel on 31 December 1966,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44223|supp=y|page=310|date=6 January 1967}}</ref> and made [[Commanding Officer]] 1st Battalion, The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders (the \u2018Argylls\u2019) on 12 January 1967.\n\n==Aden==\nIn 1967 the British Aden colony consisted of the City of Aden and attached Protectorate areas, with a total land mass similar to that of the United Kingdom. These territories enjoyed a degree of self government as the [[Federation of South Arabia]]. Within the City itself was the old quarter known as \"The Crater\", so called because it was sited in an [[extinct volcano]].<ref>Pirates to Grenades [http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/pirates.html Aden] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171058/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/pirates.html |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref> The Crater district had an area of approximately one square mile and housed approximately 80,000 inhabitants.<ref>''Having Been A Soldier'', p. 1. The figure is repeated on p. 204.</ref> Between 1963 and 1967 the British administration faced a low intensity [[guerrilla warfare|insurgency]] from groups of armed Arab nationalists who were seeking independence for Aden and competing for future power after the inevitable British withdrawal. This insurgency was designated the \"[[Aden Emergency]]\".\n\n==Uprising in Aden City==\nIn late June 1967 the 1st Battalion Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders was due to take over responsibility for security in Aden's Crater district from the [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]]. However, before this took place, on 20 June 1967 elements of the locally recruited Aden Police [[Arab Police Mutiny|mutinied]], seizing control over the district in alliance with insurgent forces, staging several ambushes of British troops in the Crater district's streets. Eight British soldiers from a transport unit were attacked and killed by the mutineers, and other British troops were killed in coordinated separate attacks. Three men from the Argylls (its Officer Commanding 'D' company, along with two privates) were killed when a patrol of the Royal Northumberland Fusiliers that they were accompanying was ambushed. All but one of the patrol being shot and killed.\n\nFor some days a stand-off around the Crater existed between British Forces and the mutineers, with the authorities hesitating. Then, just before sunset on 3 July 1967 Mitchell commanded an operation that [[Battle of the Crater (Aden)|reoccupied the Crater]]. The Argylls and other units entered and reoccupied the Crater, accompanied by 15 bagpipers playing \"[[Scotland the Brave]]\"<ref>The Argylls in Aden :[http://www.argylls1945to1971.co.uk/A_and_SH_Aden_Re-entryintoCrater.htm reocupation of the Crater]</ref> and the Argylls' regimental charge, \"Monymusk\".<ref name=ODNB>[[Tam Dalyell]], [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/63184 \u2018Mitchell, Colin Campbell (1925\u20131996)\u2019] (subscription required), ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', [[Oxford University Press]], September 2004; online edition, January 2006, {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/63184}}. Retrieved 13 February 2008</ref> Mitchell subsequently used what were described as \u201cstrong arm methods\u201d to maintain order in the Crater district for the remaining months before British withdrawal from Aden. The reoccupation itself was almost bloodless. One local man was killed and control of the Treasury building holding the [[Federation of South Arabia|Federation's]] currency reserves was restored.<ref name=\"dailyrecord.co.uk\">Daily Record, [http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/editors-choice/2008/08/23/bravery-of-mad-mitch-goes-unrewarded-despite-success-of-middle-east-mission-86908-20708289/] Mad Mitch in Aden</ref> Mitchell then used an integrated system of observation posts, patrols, checkpoints and intelligence gathering to maintain the Crater as a pacified area whilst security conditions elsewhere in Aden began to deteriorate. However, British troops in the Crater became subject to sniper and grenade attacks.\n\nAllegations were made of abuses by Mitchell and the troops under his command. There were also allegations that British troops had engaged in some looting within the district.<ref name=\"dailyrecord.co.uk\"/> Mitchell used the Chartered Bank building in the Crater district as his headquarters, and army snipers positioned upon its roof would shoot at anyone thought to represent a threat in the streets below. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] reporter stated \"Once we stood together in Crater watching the Argylls stacking, as in a butcher's shop, the bodies of four Arab militants they had just shot and Mad Mitch said: 'It was like shooting grouse, a brace here and a brace there'.\" <ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/7120629.stm|title=Return to Aden, without Mad Mitch|date=1 December 2007|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref> Mitchell (nicknamed 'Mad Mitch' by sections of the press) imposed what was described as \"Argyll law\" on the Crater.\n\nThe reoccupation of the Crater made Mitchell popular with sections of the British press and public. At the same time it brought disapproval from Mitchell's superiors in both the Army and the High Commission.<ref name=\"the Argylls' 1967 Aden campaign\">Army history :[http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm the Argylls' 1967 Aden campaign] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220801/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> He was criticized for being a publicity-seeker, and there were accusations that the troops under his command lacked discipline. One High Commission official in Aden describing the Argylls as \"a bunch of Glasgow thugs\" (a statement for which he later apologised).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm |title=The Argylls in Aden |access-date=4 September 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220801/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The reoccupation and subsequent control of the Crater district were controversial. General-Officer-Commanding Middle East Land Forces, Major-General [[Philip Tower]], feared that it would merely provoke trouble. He was of the view that engaging in a full reoccupation of the Crater, with its risk of casualties, was pointless given that British withdrawal from Aden was imminent and British strategy was moving to the role of neutral peacekeeping. Tower had authorized a probe into the Crater but Mitchell had used this authority to carry out a full military reoccupation. Tower subsequently ordered Mitchell to \"throttle back\" on the operation.<ref name=\"the Argylls' 1967 Aden campaign\"/> Mitchell stated that he considered Tower's approach to be \u201cwet hen tactics\u201d. The situation that developed was described in ''[[The Times]]'' as follows:<ref name=\"The Times, 24 July 1996\">''[[The Times]]'', 24 July 1996</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Mitchell frequently appeared on television: a small, handsome man with a direct, pugnacious manner, speaking the robust, un-minced words that the British had not heard from their army officers since the acceleration of the Imperial decline had begun nearly two decades before. Newspapers took him up as a popular hero, proudly bestowing upon him the sobriquet of 'Mad Mitch'.}}\n\nQuestions were raised in the House of Commons about the events in Aden. [[Tam Dalyell]] (Labour, West Lothian) asked whether it was true that: \"Mitchell disobeyed operational and administrative orders of his senior officers during the recapture of the Crater\"?<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 17 July 1968, \u201dIndiscipline Denied by Colonel Mitchell\u201d</ref> Mitchell himself later stated that he had been rebuked over the reoccupation by General Tower. The nature of this rebuke was explained by British Government's Defence Minister [[Denis Healey]] as follows:<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 25 July 1968</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\u2026 the brigade commander thought it necessary to emphasize to Colonel Mitchell that the maintenance of law and order with minimum force leading to an orderly withdrawal from Aden with minimum casualties was the policy that had to be followed.}}\n\nThe final British withdrawal from Aden took place in November 1967. Mitchell and the Argylls arrived back at their Plymouth garrison on 27 November. Between July and November the regiment had suffered 5 dead and 25 wounded in Aden, a near 5% casualty rate. Unlike all the other battalion commanders from Aden, Mitchell was not decorated, receiving instead only a Mention in Despatches.<ref name=MiD>{{London Gazette|issue=44508|supp=y|pages=878\u2013879|date=19 January 1968}}</ref> It was also indicated to him that further career advancement within the army was unlikely. Interviewed by the BBC in 1985, General Tower said \"Colonel Mitchell, for reasons of his own, wanted to cut a dash with the Argylls in the Crater\" thereby accepting unnecessary casualties.<ref>BBC documentary End of Empire - Aden, available on YouTube, see minute 42:30 onwards</ref> Reports began to circulate to the effect that the Argylls were to be disbanded as part of a general cutback in defence spending. In July 1968, Mitchell gave notice of his intention to resign his commission at the end of the year. Although he had not given the customary 7 months\u2019 notice required of senior officers, his resignation was accepted with effect from 1 October 1968.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44686|supp=y|page=10530|date=27 September 1968}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nOnce he was a civilian, Mitchell assumed a prominent public role in a \u201cSave the Argylls\u201d campaign to stop the abolition of the regiment. He published a memoir entitled ''Having Been a Soldier'', undertook some freelance journalism and briefly took a job as management trainee with Beaverbrook Newspapers. However, he had become a popular public figure from his time in Aden, and turned this to his advantage when he started a new career in politics. In 1969 he was adopted as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party's]] parliamentary candidate for [[Aberdeenshire West (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeenshire West]]. This was a Liberal Party held seat, although the sitting member was retiring at the next election. Mitchell took the seat<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45134|page=6951|date=23 June 1970}}</ref> with a 5,000 vote majority in the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]].<ref>1970 General Election :[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge70/i01.htm results, see Aberdeenshire West]</ref> His main opponent in that election was [[Laura Miranda Grimond|Laura Grimond]], wife of former Liberal leader [[Jo Grimond]].\n\nHe proved to be an energetic and effective constituency M.P. He also served for a year as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]. However, it became apparent that he was not likely to develop a ministerial career. His main political interest was the British Army, and he was frequently critical of its leadership. In August 1970 he was quoted as having referred to \"... those bastards in Whitehall\".<ref>The Times, 7 August 1970, \u201cEmaciated Thin Red Line Survives\u201d</ref> He gravitated towards the right wing of the Conservative Party, opposing the United Kingdom's membership of the [[European Economic Community]], economic sanctions being placed upon [[Rhodesia]], and the arms embargo on Israel. He also became a prominent member of both the [[Monday Club]] and the 'Anglo-Rhodesian Society'. Mitchell became known as a maverick M.P., and was one of 39 Conservatives who defied the Party whip to vote against entry to the [[European Community|EEC]] in the Commons vote on 28 October 1971.<ref>BBC report :[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7948612.stm voting on the EU]</ref> Although never promoted to ministerial office, Mitchell was a high-profile backbench M.P., in demand by society and the media. He was a popular member of the [[Garrick Club]], and was reported to enjoy a \u201cgregarious social life\u201d in London.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 25 July 1996</ref>\n\nIn 1973 he was approached by a consortium that was planning to establish a large sporting and agricultural estate in Scotland, which invited him to take a stake in the project and become the project's General-Manager with a generous salary. Mitchell accepted and announced he would not be seeking re-election to Parliament on the basis that he \u201c\u2026could not afford to be an M.P.\u201d \u2014 a remark that would come back to haunt him.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 16 January 1974</ref> He left Parliament at the time of the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]], against the advice of both his wife Sue and fellow maverick M.P [[Tam Dalyell]].\n\n==1974-1989==\nThe Scottish estate project failed and Mitchell became unemployed. He later stated that giving up his seat in Parliament had been a disastrous mistake. Mitchell spent much of the next 10 years trying to get back into Parliament. He applied to several constituency Conservative Associations, including [[Bournemouth East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth East]] in August 1977, but at every selection interview the question was raised as to why he had given up Aberdeenshire West in 1974. No winnable constituency would adopt him.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 25 August 1977</ref> He remained on the fringes of Conservative Party politics, ''The Times'' Diary columnist reporting on a meeting of the Monday Club at the 1976 Conservative Party conference where he had made a speech on the subject of Rhodesia:<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 8 October 1976</ref>\n\n{{cquote|I went to mock, but came away with much sympathy for Mitchell personally rather than for the lost cause he espouses. He is quite at odds with the world in which he finds himself}}\n\nDuring this period Mitchell remained sporadically active in a series of consultancies, mostly of a military or security nature. He is known to have provided services to backers of the [[Mujahideen]] insurgents in [[Afghanistan]] and [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in [[Nicaragua]].<ref>New York Times :[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/27/world/colin-mitchell-is-dead-at-70-british-hero-in-aden-battles.html Mitchell's 1996 obituary]</ref> In November 1980, Mitchell praised the Mujahideen as \"gallant fighters... expressing themselves, as Afghans know best, in the romantic tradition of sniping, raiding and brigandry.\" He urged Western leaders to provide them with military training and equipment, and to select \"proven guerilla fighters\" from their ranks for training as future leaders of Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news|first=Colin|last=Mitchell|title=Aid for Afghan resistance|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=29 November 1980|page=13|issue=60789}}</ref> However, Mitchell became increasingly dissatisfied with his situation.<ref name=\"The Times, 24 July 1996\"/>\n\n{{cquote|At times his disappointment showed and it amounted to bitterness. He turned angrily against the media, which he had used so brilliantly... and against old friends who had tried to help him in difficult times. Once a popular member of the Garrick Club, he avoided it for years, finally stopping his subscription.}}\n\n==The Halo Trust==\nIn 1989, Mitchell took a leading role in the [[Halo Trust]] (the hazardous areas life-support organization). This non-profit making organization undertook de-mining operations in former war zones. It employed a core of (mostly British and Commonwealth) de-mining experts and a large number of locally recruited and trained personnel. Most of the Halo personnel were former servicemen.<ref>Halo Trust :[http://www.halotrust.org/index.html website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331131155/http://www.halotrust.org/index.html |date=31 March 2008 }}</ref> Halo became active around the world in areas such as [[Mozambique]], [[Cambodia]] and Afghanistan. Mitchell appeared comfortable in his work with Halo. It raised his public profile once again, and in a manner that was both positive and uncontroversial.\n\n==Death==\nMitchell died in his 71st year on 20 July 1996 at [[Westminster]] in London, after a short illness. His obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' was written by his friend the Labour MP [[Tam Dalyell]]. Dalyell stated :\n\n{{cquote|In the course of my last conversation with him in 1995 Mitchell said that in perspective the \"Mad Mitch\" image had ruined his prospects of a serious senior military career, and had deprived him of being taken seriously as a politician ...}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMitchell married Jean Hamilton (Sue) Phillips in April 1956. Phillips was the daughter of Wing Commander Stephen Phillips, R.A.F., and was a native of Meikleour, Perthshire. The couple had three children (2 sons and 1 daughter), the youngest of whom (Colina) was born in 1965. Their son, Dr. Angus Mitchell, is a noted authority on the life of Irish revolutionary [[Roger Casement]].<ref>Irish democrat :[http://www.irishdemocrat.co.uk/greaves-summer-school/2006-greaves-summer-school/ see 5th image]</ref>  One observer later described Phillips as: \"his marvellous wife ... who backed him through thick and thin - mostly thin\".<ref>''[[The Independent]]'' obituary :[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19960724/ai_n14059912/pg_1 Lt-Col Colin Mitchell, by Tam Dalyell - 24 July 1996]</ref>\n\n==References==\nThe two major sources for the article are ''Having Been a Soldier'' (Mitchell's autobiography) London: Hamilton, 1969. {{ISBN|0-241-01722-X}}, and from Tam Dalyell's long obituary [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary--ltcol-colin-mitchell-1330247.html] of Mitchell published in ''[[The Independent]]'' on 24 July 1996.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Colin Campbell Mitchell}}\n* Army History [https://web.archive.org/web/20071210113504/http://www.argylls1945to1971.co.uk/index.html The Argylls, 1945 to 1971]\n* 700 [[Glengarry|Glengarried]] Men :[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220801/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm The Argylls' 1967 tour of duty in Aden]\n* BBC report, 1 December 2007:[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/7120629.stm a return to Aden without Mad Mitch]\n* Army History  [http://www.argylls1945to1971.co.uk/A_and_SH_Aden1967.htm Argylls in Aden]\n* \"Tartan kitsch\" {{YouTube|ex4J6X8kIts|The Barren Rocks of Aden}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aberdeenshire West (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeenshire West]]\n  | years  = [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\u2013[[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|Feb 1974]]\n  | before = [[James Davidson (UK politician)|James Davidson]]\n  | after  = [[Russell Fairgrieve]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Colin}}\n[[Category:Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Aden Emergency]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Cyprus Emergency]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Palestine Emergency]]\n[[Category:Scottish Conservative Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Whitgift School]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:King's African Rifles officers]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Staff College, Camberley]]\n[[Category:People from Croydon]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the cricketer|Colin Mitchell (cricketer)}}\n{{distinguish|Collin Mitchell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n<!--as Colin Mitchell redirects here-->\n{{Infobox military person \n|name=Colin Campbell Mitchell\n|birth_date= 17 November 1925\n|death_date= 20 July 1996 (aged 70)\n|birth_place= [[Croydon]], [[Surrey]], England\n|death_place= [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|placeofburial= \n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Colin Campbell Mitchell.jpg\n|caption=Colin Mitchell c.1967 \n|nickname=Mad Mitch\n|allegiance={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch={{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears=1943\u20131968\n|rank=[[Lieutenant Colonel]]\n|commands= 1st Battalion, [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]]\n|battles=[[World War II]]<br/>[[Palestine Emergency]]<br/>[[Korean War]]<br>[[Cyprus Emergency]]<br/>[[Indonesia\u2013Malaysia confrontation]]<br/>[[Aden Emergency]]\n|laterwork=[[Member of Parliament]]<br/>Founder of the [[Halo Trust]]}}\n\n'''Colin Campbell Mitchell''' (17 November 1925 \u2013 20 July 1996) was a [[British Army]] soldier and politician. He became a public figure in 1967 as the commanding officer of the 1st Battalion of the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]]. Forces under his command reoccupied the Crater district of Aden which had been taken over by local police mutineers in what became known as [[Battle of the Crater (Aden)|\"the last battle of the British empire\"]]. The reoccupation and subsequent control of the Crater were controversial and Mitchell resigned his army commission in 1968. Subsequently he became a Conservative Member of Parliament and served one term from 1970 to February 1974. After participation in a failed business venture he subsequently worked as a security and military consultant. In 1989 Mitchell took a leading role in the [[Halo Trust]], a not-for-profit organisation undertaking mine clearance in former war zones.\n\n==Early life==\nMitchell\u2019s father (also called Colin) came from an Argyllshire fishing family. Mitchell (Snr) worked in a solicitor's office and for the [[David MacBrayne Ltd|MacBrayne ferry company]] before serving in the 10th Battalion Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders in [[World War I]]. Mitchell (Snr) achieved the rank of captain (commissioned \u2018in the field\u2019) and was awarded the [[Military Cross]] at the [[Second Battle of Ypres]], but when the young Colin asked him how he would only say, 'Oh, shooting rabbits'. He was badly gassed in 1918. After the war, he worked in the City of London and married a [[Glaswegian]] woman (n\u00e9e Gilmour) whose father worked as a manager for the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LMS]] Railway company. The couple took up residence in the South London suburb of [[Purley, London|Purley]] where they had two children \u2013 Colin and Henrietta. The family lived in a modest semi-detached house and Colin would attend services at the local [[Presbyterian]] Church wearing a [[kilt]].<ref>''[[The Independent]]'', obituary, early paragraphs on family history in 'free to view' section :[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19960724/ai_n14059912/pg_1 Lt-Col Colin Mitchell], by [[Tam Dalyell]] - 24 July 1996</ref> Mitchell received his formal education at the [[Whitgift School|Whitgift Grammar School]] in [[Croydon]].\n\n==Military career==\nIn 1940, at age 15, Mitchell enlisted in the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]], and may have been the youngest Home Guard soldier. In May 1943 he joined the [[British Army]], enlisting as a private in the [[Royal West Kent Regiment]]. He soon became a Lance-Corporal and instructed newcomers in physical training. One of his fellow instructors was [[Stan Cullis]] who had been the captain of the [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]] [[1939 FA Cup Final|cup side at Wembley in 1939]] and was the captain of [[England national football team|England]] at the time. Mitchell was commissioned into the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]] in 1944.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36843|supp=y|page=5788|date=15 December 1944}}</ref> He fought in the final battles of the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian campaign]], and was lightly wounded in the advance on [[Ferrara]]. Despite this, his wartime experience inclined him to take up a military career.<ref>''[[The Independent]]'', obituary :[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary--ltcol-colin-mitchell-1330247.html Lt-Col Colin Mitchell], by [[Tam Dalyell]] - 24 July 1996</ref>  He was appointed to a regular commission on 21 December 1946.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37823|supp=y|page=6169|date=17 December 1946}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the war, he saw action against Jewish guerrillas during the [[Jewish insurgency in Palestine|Palestine Emergency]]. While in Palestine, he participated in operations to arrest Jewish militants. During [[Operation Agatha]], which saw most of the Jewish political leadership in Palestine detained, Mitchell's mission was to arrest [[Moshe Sharett|Moshe Shertok]] (a future [[Prime Minister of Israel]]). Initially, his unit raided the wrong house. However, they were later able to find and arrest him. In July 1946, he witnessed the [[King David Hotel bombing]]: he and his company commander were within 300 feet of the building when the bombing occurred. While on a personal reconnaissance mission, he was shot and wounded by one of his own Bren gunners, who mistook him for a guerrilla. After recovering from his injuries, he was transferred from his regiment to become [[aide-de-camp]] to General [[Gordon Holmes MacMillan|Gordon MacMillan]], the commander of British forces in Palestine and Transjordan. He spent a total of three years in Palestine. While there, he made friends among both the Arabs and Jews, including [[Moshe Dayan]], a future Israeli general who would become one of Mitchell's heroes, as well as Moshe Shertok, who developed a cordial relationship with Mitchell after his arrest and corresponded with him for years afterward, when he became a senior Israeli government official.<ref>http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/nov/17/northern-ireland-compton-committees</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/army-obituaries/5796166/Lt-Col-C-C-Mad-Mitch-Mitchell.html Lt-Col C C 'Mad Mitch' Mitchell]</ref>\n\nIn 1950, with the outbreak of the [[Korean War]], he was allowed to rejoin his regiment so he could deploy to Korea. He participated in the initial advance into [[North Korea]], seeing close-quarters combat along the way. His regiment ultimately reached [[Taechon]], near the Chinese border on the [[Yalu River]]. When the Chinese Army intervened and crossed the Yalu River in overwhelming numbers, the regiment was forced to take part in the retreat of UN forces, and later helped hold the line against Communist forces when UN forces consolidated. The regiment held a position known as \"Frostbite Ridge\", where they had to endure freezing conditions. They held the area through the winter until the thaw, and in 1951, they began to advance. However, shortly afterward, they were relieved and withdrawn.<ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\"/>\n\nFollowing his service in Korea, Mitchell was posted in Britain, but in late 1957, he returned to the Argylls as a company commander with the 1st Battalion, and was posted to [[Cyprus]]. At the time, the [[Cyprus Emergency]] was in full swing. Mitchell was placed in charge of the coastal towns of [[Paphos]] and Ktima, where his men engaged in counter-insurgency operations against [[EOKA]] guerrillas. They faced both conventional EOKA raids and forest fires deliberately lit by EOKA fighters and local villagers who were motivated by the money they would receive to fight them.<ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\"/><ref>Edwards, Aaron: ''Mad Mitch's Tribal Law: Aden and the End of Empire''</ref>\n\nMitchell was subsequently posted to the [[British Army of the Rhine]] with the rest of the regiment, and then joined the [[King's African Rifles]], and was posted to [[East Africa]]. Soon afterward, he saw action in [[Zanzibar]] with the KAR in breaking up disturbances between the island's Arab and African populations, which had begun during a general election and had descended into widespread rioting and clashes. He also participated in operations on the [[Northern Frontier District]]. At the time, Somali guerrillas were launching raids as part of a campaign to unite the region with Somalia, and the frontiers with other neighbouring states were also volatile. In one incident, Mitchell was searching for Somali guerrillas in a low-flying helicopter, and an elephant attempted to attack the helicopter, nearly clipping it with its tusks. It has been claimed that while with the KAR Mitchell was instrumental in obtaining a commission for [[Idi Amin]], who later became President of [[Uganda]]. Mitchell's familiarity with the Scottish [[Scottish clan|clan system]] made him more comfortable with African tribal issues than was the case with his English contemporaries. Impressed by Mitchell and other Scottish officers, Amin would later adopt the title [[The Last King of Scotland|''King of Scotland'']].<ref name=\"Telegraph obituary\"/><ref>''[[The New York Times]]'':[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/27/world/colin-mitchell-is-dead-at-70-british-hero-in-aden-battles.html Mitchell's 1996 obituary]</ref>\n\nFollowing his service in Kenya, Mitchell rejoined the Argylls, which was sent to [[Borneo]] to participate in the [[Indonesian-Malaysian Confrontation]]. Mitchell participated in a series of clashes with Indonesian forces. After six months of jungle warfare, the regiment was sent back to [[Singapore]] to recuperate. Mitchell was posted back to the UK as a staff officer. Throughout all this time Mitchell was making a reputation as a bold and efficient officer, passing out top of [[Staff College, Camberley|Staff College]] and serving as GSO1 on the staff of [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence staff]], [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Lord Mountbatten]]. Mitchell was promoted [[First Lieutenant|lieutenant]] in 1947,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38240|page=1926|date=16 March 1948}}</ref> [[captain (OF-2)|captain]] in 1952,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39696|supp=y|page=6068|date=14 November 1952}}</ref> [[major (United Kingdom)|major]] in 1959,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41868|supp=y|page=7246|date=13 November 1959}}</ref> and his success in a wide range of appointments won him [[brevet rank]] as a lieutenant-colonel in 1964.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=43371|supp=y|page=5715|date=30 June 1964}}</ref>\n\nMitchell was promoted to substantive lieutenant-colonel on 31 December 1966,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44223|supp=y|page=310|date=6 January 1967}}</ref> and made [[Commanding Officer]] 1st Battalion, The Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders (the \u2018Argylls\u2019) on 12 January 1967.\n\n==Aden==\nIn 1967 the British Aden colony consisted of the City of Aden and attached Protectorate areas, with a total land mass similar to that of the United Kingdom. These territories enjoyed a degree of self government as the [[Federation of South Arabia]]. Within the City itself was the old quarter known as \"The Crater\", so called because it was sited in an [[extinct volcano]].<ref>Pirates to Grenades [http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/pirates.html Aden] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171058/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/pirates.html |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref> The Crater district had an area of approximately one square mile and housed approximately 80,000 inhabitants.<ref>''Having Been A Soldier'', p. 1. The figure is repeated on p. 204.</ref> Between 1963 and 1967 the British administration faced a low intensity [[guerrilla warfare|insurgency]] from groups of armed Arab nationalists who were seeking independence for Aden and competing for future power after the inevitable British withdrawal. This insurgency was designated the \"[[Aden Emergency]]\".\n\n==Uprising in Aden City==\nIn late June 1967 the 1st Battalion Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders was due to take over responsibility for security in Aden's Crater district from the [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]]. However, before this took place, on 20 June 1967 elements of the locally recruited Aden Police [[Arab Police Mutiny|mutinied]], seizing control over the district in alliance with insurgent forces, staging several ambushes of British troops in the Crater district's streets. Eight British soldiers from a transport unit were attacked and killed by the mutineers, and other British troops were killed in coordinated separate attacks. Three men from the Argylls (its Officer Commanding 'D' company, along with two privates) were killed when a patrol of the Royal Northumberland Fusiliers that they were accompanying was ambushed. All but one of the patrol being shot and killed.\n\nFor some days a stand-off around the Crater existed between British Forces and the mutineers, with the authorities hesitating. Then, just before sunset on 3 July 1967 Mitchell commanded an operation that [[Battle of the Crater (Aden)|reoccupied the Crater]]. The Argylls and other units entered and reoccupied the Crater, accompanied by 15 bagpipers playing \"[[Scotland the Brave]]\"<ref>The Argylls in Aden :[http://www.argylls1945to1971.co.uk/A_and_SH_Aden_Re-entryintoCrater.htm reocupation of the Crater]</ref> and the Argylls' regimental charge, \"Monymusk\".<ref name=ODNB>[[Tam Dalyell]], [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/63184 \u2018Mitchell, Colin Campbell (1925\u20131996)\u2019] (subscription required), ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', [[Oxford University Press]], September 2004; online edition, January 2006, {{doi|10.1093/ref:odnb/63184}}. Retrieved 13 February 2008</ref> Mitchell subsequently used what were described as \u201cstrong arm methods\u201d to maintain order in the Crater district for the remaining months before British withdrawal from Aden. The reoccupation itself was almost bloodless. One local man was killed and control of the Treasury building holding the [[Federation of South Arabia|Federation's]] currency reserves was restored.<ref name=\"dailyrecord.co.uk\">Daily Record, [http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/editors-choice/2008/08/23/bravery-of-mad-mitch-goes-unrewarded-despite-success-of-middle-east-mission-86908-20708289/] Mad Mitch in Aden</ref> Mitchell then used an integrated system of observation posts, patrols, checkpoints and intelligence gathering to maintain the Crater as a pacified area whilst security conditions elsewhere in Aden began to deteriorate. However, British troops in the Crater became subject to sniper and grenade attacks.\n\nAllegations were made of abuses by Mitchell and the troops under his command. There were also allegations that British troops had engaged in some looting within the district.<ref name=\"dailyrecord.co.uk\"/> Mitchell used the Chartered Bank building in the Crater district as his headquarters, and army snipers positioned upon its roof would shoot at anyone thought to represent a threat in the streets below. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] reporter stated \"Once we stood together in Crater watching the Argylls stacking, as in a butcher's shop, the bodies of four Arab militants they had just shot and Mad Mitch said: 'It was like shooting grouse, a brace here and a brace there'.\" <ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/7120629.stm|title=Return to Aden, without Mad Mitch|date=1 December 2007|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref> Mitchell (nicknamed 'Mad Mitch' by sections of the press) imposed what was described as \"Argyll law\" on the Crater.\n\nThe reoccupation of the Crater made Mitchell popular with sections of the British press and public. At the same time it brought disapproval from Mitchell's superiors in both the Army and the High Commission.<ref name=\"the Argylls' 1967 Aden campaign\">Army history :[http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm the Argylls' 1967 Aden campaign] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220801/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm |date=27 September 2007 }}</ref> He was criticized for being a publicity-seeker, and there were accusations that the troops under his command lacked discipline. One High Commission official in Aden describing the Argylls as \"a bunch of Glasgow thugs\" (a statement for which he later apologised).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm |title=The Argylls in Aden |access-date=4 September 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220801/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The reoccupation and subsequent control of the Crater district were controversial. General-Officer-Commanding Middle East Land Forces, Major-General [[Philip Tower]], feared that it would merely provoke trouble. He was of the view that engaging in a full reoccupation of the Crater, with its risk of casualties, was pointless given that British withdrawal from Aden was imminent and British strategy was moving to the role of neutral peacekeeping. Tower had authorized a probe into the Crater but Mitchell had used this authority to carry out a full military reoccupation. Tower subsequently ordered Mitchell to \"throttle back\" on the operation.<ref name=\"the Argylls' 1967 Aden campaign\"/> Mitchell stated that he considered Tower\u2019s approach to be \u201cwet hen tactics\u201d. The situation that developed was described in ''[[The Times]]'' as follows:<ref name=\"The Times, 24 July 1996\">''[[The Times]]'', 24 July 1996</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Mitchell frequently appeared on television: a small, handsome man with a direct, pugnacious manner, speaking the robust, un-minced words that the British had not heard from their army officers since the acceleration of the Imperial decline had begun nearly two decades before. Newspapers took him up as a popular hero, proudly bestowing upon him the sobriquet of 'Mad Mitch'.}}\n\nQuestions were raised in the House of Commons about the events in Aden. [[Tam Dalyell]] (Labour, West Lothian) asked whether it was true that: \"Mitchell disobeyed operational and administrative orders of his senior officers during the recapture of the Crater\"?<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 17 July 1968, \u201dIndiscipline Denied by Colonel Mitchell\u201d</ref> Mitchell himself later stated that he had been rebuked over the reoccupation by General Tower. The nature of this rebuke was explained by British Government's Defence Minister [[Denis Healey]] as follows:<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 25 July 1968</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\u2026 the brigade commander thought it necessary to emphasize to Colonel Mitchell that the maintenance of law and order with minimum force leading to an orderly withdrawal from Aden with minimum casualties was the policy that had to be followed.}}\n\nThe final British withdrawal from Aden took place in November 1967. Mitchell and the Argylls arrived back at their Plymouth garrison on 27 November. Between July and November the regiment had suffered 5 dead and 25 wounded in Aden, a near 5% casualty rate. Unlike all the other battalion commanders from Aden, Mitchell was not decorated, receiving instead only a Mention in Despatches.<ref name=MiD>{{London Gazette|issue=44508|supp=y|pages=878\u2013879|date=19 January 1968}}</ref> It was also indicated to him that further career advancement within the army was unlikely. Interviewed by the BBC in 1985, General Tower said \"Colonel Mitchell, for reasons of his own, wanted to cut a dash with the Argylls in the Crater\" thereby accepting unnecessary casualties.<ref>BBC documentary End of Empire - Aden, available on YouTube, see minute 42:30 onwards</ref> Reports began to circulate to the effect that the Argylls were to be disbanded as part of a general cutback in defence spending. In July 1968, Mitchell gave notice of his intention to resign his commission at the end of the year. Although he had not given the customary 7 months\u2019 notice required of senior officers, his resignation was accepted with effect from 1 October 1968.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44686|supp=y|page=10530|date=27 September 1968}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nOnce he was a civilian, Mitchell assumed a prominent public role in a \u201cSave the Argylls\u201d campaign to stop the abolition of the regiment. He published a memoir entitled ''Having Been a Soldier'', undertook some freelance journalism and briefly took a job as management trainee with Beaverbrook Newspapers. However, he had become a popular public figure from his time in Aden, and turned this to his advantage when he started a new career in politics. In 1969 he was adopted as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party's]] parliamentary candidate for [[Aberdeenshire West (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeenshire West]]. This was a Liberal Party held seat, although the sitting member was retiring at the next election. Mitchell took the seat<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45134|page=6951|date=23 June 1970}}</ref> with a 5,000 vote majority in the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]].<ref>1970 General Election :[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge70/i01.htm results, see Aberdeenshire West]</ref> His main opponent in that election was [[Laura Miranda Grimond|Laura Grimond]], wife of former Liberal leader [[Jo Grimond]].\n\nHe proved to be an energetic and effective constituency M.P. He also served for a year as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]. However, it became apparent that he was not likely to develop a ministerial career. His main political interest was the British Army, and he was frequently critical of its leadership. In August 1970 he was quoted as having referred to \"... those bastards in Whitehall\".<ref>The Times, 7 August 1970, \u201cEmaciated Thin Red Line Survives\u201d</ref> He gravitated towards the right wing of the Conservative Party, opposing the United Kingdom's membership of the [[European Economic Community]], economic sanctions being placed upon [[Rhodesia]], and the arms embargo on Israel. He also became a prominent member of both the [[Monday Club]] and the 'Anglo-Rhodesian Society'. Mitchell became known as a maverick M.P., and was one of 39 Conservatives who defied the Party whip to vote against entry to the [[European Community|EEC]] in the Commons vote on 28 October 1971.<ref>BBC report :[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7948612.stm voting on the EU]</ref> Although never promoted to ministerial office, Mitchell was a high-profile backbench M.P., in demand by society and the media. He was a popular member of the [[Garrick Club]], and was reported to enjoy a \u201cgregarious social life\u201d in London.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 25 July 1996</ref>\n\nIn 1973 he was approached by a consortium that was planning to establish a large sporting and agricultural estate in Scotland, which invited him to take a stake in the project and become the project's General-Manager with a generous salary. Mitchell accepted and announced he would not be seeking re-election to Parliament on the basis that he \u201c\u2026could not afford to be an M.P.\u201d \u2014 a remark that would come back to haunt him.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 16 January 1974</ref> He left Parliament at the time of the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]], against the advice of both his wife Sue and fellow maverick M.P [[Tam Dalyell]].\n\n==1974-1989==\nThe Scottish estate project failed and Mitchell became unemployed. He later stated that giving up his seat in Parliament had been a disastrous mistake. Mitchell spent much of the next 10 years trying to get back into Parliament. He applied to several constituency Conservative Associations, including [[Bournemouth East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth East]] in August 1977, but at every selection interview the question was raised as to why he had given up Aberdeenshire West in 1974. No winnable constituency would adopt him.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 25 August 1977</ref> He remained on the fringes of Conservative Party politics, ''The Times'' Diary columnist reporting on a meeting of the Monday Club at the 1976 Conservative Party conference where he had made a speech on the subject of Rhodesia:<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 8 October 1976</ref>\n\n{{cquote|I went to mock, but came away with much sympathy for Mitchell personally rather than for the lost cause he espouses. He is quite at odds with the world in which he finds himself}}\n\nDuring this period Mitchell remained sporadically active in a series of consultancies, mostly of a military or security nature. He is known to have provided services to backers of the [[Mujahideen]] insurgents in [[Afghanistan]] and [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in [[Nicaragua]].<ref>New York Times :[https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/27/world/colin-mitchell-is-dead-at-70-british-hero-in-aden-battles.html Mitchell's 1996 obituary]</ref> In November 1980, Mitchell praised the Mujahideen as \"gallant fighters... expressing themselves, as Afghans know best, in the romantic tradition of sniping, raiding and brigandry.\" He urged Western leaders to provide them with military training and equipment, and to select \"proven guerilla fighters\" from their ranks for training as future leaders of Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news|first=Colin|last=Mitchell|title=Aid for Afghan resistance|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=29 November 1980|page=13|issue=60789}}</ref> However, Mitchell became increasingly dissatisfied with his situation.<ref name=\"The Times, 24 July 1996\"/>\n\n{{cquote|At times his disappointment showed and it amounted to bitterness. He turned angrily against the media, which he had used so brilliantly... and against old friends who had tried to help him in difficult times. Once a popular member of the Garrick Club, he avoided it for years, finally stopping his subscription.}}\n\n==The Halo Trust==\nIn 1989, Mitchell took a leading role in the [[Halo Trust]] (the hazardous areas life-support organization). This non-profit making organization undertook de-mining operations in former war zones. It employed a core of (mostly British and Commonwealth) de-mining experts and a large number of locally recruited and trained personnel. Most of the Halo personnel were former servicemen.<ref>Halo Trust :[http://www.halotrust.org/index.html website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331131155/http://www.halotrust.org/index.html |date=31 March 2008 }}</ref> Halo became active around the world in areas such as [[Mozambique]], [[Cambodia]] and Afghanistan. Mitchell appeared comfortable in his work with Halo. It raised his public profile once again, and in a manner that was both positive and uncontroversial.\n\n==Death==\nMitchell died in his 71st year on 20 July 1996 at [[Westminster]] in London, after a short illness. His obituary in ''[[The Independent]]'' was written by his friend the Labour MP [[Tam Dalyell]]. Dalyell stated :\n\n{{cquote|In the course of my last conversation with him in 1995 Mitchell said that in perspective the \"Mad Mitch\" image had ruined his prospects of a serious senior military career, and had deprived him of being taken seriously as a politician ...}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMitchell married Jean Hamilton (Sue) Phillips in April 1956. Phillips was the daughter of Wing Commander Stephen Phillips, R.A.F., and was a native of Meikleour, Perthshire. The couple had three children (2 sons and 1 daughter), the youngest of whom (Colina) was born in 1965. Their son, Dr. Angus Mitchell, is a noted authority on the life of Irish revolutionary [[Roger Casement]].<ref>Irish democrat :[http://www.irishdemocrat.co.uk/greaves-summer-school/2006-greaves-summer-school/ see 5th image]</ref>  One observer later described Phillips as: \"his marvellous wife ... who backed him through thick and thin - mostly thin\".<ref>''[[The Independent]]'' obituary :[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19960724/ai_n14059912/pg_1 Lt-Col Colin Mitchell, by Tam Dalyell - 24 July 1996]</ref>\n\n==References==\nThe two major sources for the article are ''Having Been a Soldier'' (Mitchell's autobiography) London: Hamilton, 1969. {{ISBN|0-241-01722-X}}, and from Tam Dalyell's long obituary [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary--ltcol-colin-mitchell-1330247.html] of Mitchell published in ''[[The Independent]]'' on 24 July 1996.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Colin Campbell Mitchell}}\n* Army History [https://web.archive.org/web/20071210113504/http://www.argylls1945to1971.co.uk/index.html The Argylls, 1945 to 1971]\n* 700 [[Glengarry|Glengarried]] Men :[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220801/http://www.britains-smallwars.com/Aden/700.htm The Argylls' 1967 tour of duty in Aden]\n* BBC report, 1 December 2007:[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/7120629.stm a return to Aden without Mad Mitch]\n* Army History  [http://www.argylls1945to1971.co.uk/A_and_SH_Aden1967.htm Argylls in Aden]\n* \"Tartan kitsch\" {{YouTube|ex4J6X8kIts|The Barren Rocks of Aden}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Aberdeenshire West (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeenshire West]]\n  | years  = [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\u2013[[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|Feb 1974]]\n  | before = [[James Davidson (UK politician)|James Davidson]]\n  | after  = [[Russell Fairgrieve]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Colin}}\n[[Category:Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Aden Emergency]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Cyprus Emergency]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Palestine Emergency]]\n[[Category:Scottish Conservative Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Whitgift School]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:King's African Rifles officers]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Staff College, Camberley]]\n[[Category:People from Croydon]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Subsequently \u2192 Subsequently,, \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colin_Mitchell"}
{"title_page": "Phantom vibration syndrome", "text_new": "'''Phantom vibration syndrome''' or '''phantom ringing syndrome''' is the perception that one's [[mobile phone]] is [[Vibrating alert|vibrating]] or ringing when it is not. Other terms for this concept include '''ringxiety''' (a [['' (a [[portmanteau]] of ''phone'' and ''phantom'').<ref name=\"Goodman\">{{cite news|last=Goodman|first=Brenda|title=I Hear Ringing and There's No One There. I Wonder Why.|work=The New York Times|page=1|date=4 May 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/04/fashion/thursdaystyles/04phan.html}}</ref> According to Dr. Michael Rothberg, the term is not a syndrome, but is better characterised as a tactile hallucination since the brain perceives a sensation that is not actually present.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title = Phantom vibration syndrome among medical staff: a cross sectional survey|journal = BMJ|pages = c6914|volume = 341|issue = dec15 2|doi = 10.1136/bmj.c6914|pmid = 21159761|first = M. B.|last = Rothberg|first2 = A.|last2 = Arora|first3 = J.|last3 = Hermann|first4 = R.|last4 = Kleppel|first5 = P. S.|last5 = Marie|first6 = P.|last6 = Visintainer|year = 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"PhonetomFischer\">{{cite web | url= https://www.facebook.com/elli.fischer/posts/10106394546200008| title= Phonetom u vsn writr any thing there wikepedia a-to-z-guides/news/20160111/phones-phantom-vibration|title=Do You Have 'Phantom Vibration Syndrome'?|last=Locke|first=Tim|website=WebMD|language=en|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> Several other articles have been published in 2010s, including in NPR, Bustle, CBS News, and Psychology Today. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2013/09/30/226820044/phantom-phone-vibrations-so-common-they-ve-changed-our-brains|title=Phantom Phone Vibrations: So Common They've Changed Our Brains?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/what-is-phantom-ringing-syndrome-youve-almost-certainly-experienced-it-before-15539483|title=Phantom Ringing Syndrome Is The Weird AF Condition You've Had But Never Heard Of|last=Hills|first=Megan C.|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/phantom-vibration-syndrome-common-in-cellphone-users/|title=\"Phantom vibration syndrome\" common in cellphone users|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/rewired-the-psychology-technology/201305/phantom-pocket-vibration-syndrome|title=Phantom Pocket Vibration Syndrome|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n\nPhantom ringing may be experienced while taking a shower, watching television, or using a noisy device. Humans are particularly sensitive to auditory tones between 1,000 and 6,000 [[hertz]], and basic mobile phone ringtones often fall within this range.<ref name=\"Goodman\"/> Phantom vibrations develop after carrying a cell phone set to use [[vibrating alert]]s.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Researcher [[Michelle Drouin]] found that almost 9 of 10 undergraduates at her college experienced phantom vibrations.<ref name=\"twsPsychologyToday\">{{cite web | url= http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/rewired-the-psychology-technology/201305/phantom-pocket-vibration-syndrome| title= Phantom Pocket Vibration Syndrome| publisher= Psychology Today| date= May 7, 2013 | accessdate= September 10, 2014| quote=...According to Dr. Michelle Drouin... 89% of the undergraduates in her study had experienced these phantom vibrations...| author=  Rosen, Larry}}</ref>{{mcn|date=November 2017}}\n\n==History==\nIn the comic strip ''[[Dilbert]]'', cartoonist [[Scott Adams]] referenced such a sensation in 1996 as \"phantom-pager syndrome\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dilbert.com/strips/comic/1996-09-16/ |title=Dilbert |last=Adams |first=Scott |date=September 16, 1996 |accessdate=October 16, 2013}}</ref> The earliest published use of the term ''phantom vibration syndrome'' dates to 2003 in an article entitled \"Phantom Vibration Syndrome\" published in the ''[[New Pittsburgh Courier]]'', written under a pen name of columnist Robert D. Jones. However, it is debated whether earlier noting of the onsets of PVS came from Michael J Lewis of Melbourne, Australia. In the conclusion of the article, Jones wrote, \"...should we be concerned about what our mind or body may be trying to tell us by the aggravating imaginary emanations from belts, pockets and even purses? Whether PVS is the result of physical nerve damage, a mental health issue, or both, this growing phenomenon seems to indicate that we may have crossed a line in this 'always on' society.\"\n\nThe first study of the phenomenon was conducted in 2007 by a researcher who coined the term ''ringxiety'' to describe it.<ref name=\"deb2014\">{{cite journal |authors=Deb A |title=Phantom vibration and phantom ringing among mobile phone users: A systematic review of literature |journal=Asia Pac Psychiatry |volume= 7|issue= 3|pages= 231\u20139|year=2014 |pmid=25408384 |doi=10.1111/appy.12164}}</ref> In 2012, the term ''phantom vibration syndrome'' was chosen as the Australian ''[[Macquarie Dictionary]]''{{'}}s word of the year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.crikey.com.au/fullysic/2013/02/07/phantom-vibration-syndrome-word-of-the-year/ |title=Phantom vibration syndrome: Word of the Year |last=Wilson |first=Aidan |work=Crikey.com.au |date=February 7, 2013 |accessdate=October 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.macquariedictionary.com.au/resources/view/word/of/the/year/|title = Macquarie Dictionary word of the year archives|last = Meacham|first = Merle|accessdate = March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nThe cause of phantom vibrations is not known.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Preliminary research suggests it is related to over-involvement with one's cell phone.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Vibrations typically begin occurring after carrying a phone for between one month and one year.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> It has been suggested that, when anticipating a phone call, the [[cerebral cortex]] may misinterpret other sensory input (such as [[muscle contractions]], pressure from clothing, or music) as a phone vibration or ring tone.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> This may be understood as a human signal detection issue, with potentially significant influences from psychological attributes.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\"> Kruger, D. J., & Djerf, J. M. (2016). High Ringxiety: Attachment Anxiety Predicts Experiences of Phantom Cell Phone Ringing. Cyberpsychology, Behavior & Social Networking, 19(1), 56-59. </ref> Factors such as experiences, expectations, and psychological states influence the threshold for signal detection.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\" /> Some phantom vibration experiences may be a type of [[pareidolia]] and can therefore be examined as a psychological phenomenon influenced by individual variances in personality, condition, and context.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\" /> Attachment anxiety can also be seen as a predictor for the frequency of phantom vibration experiences since it is associated with psychological attributes related to insecurity in interpersonal relationships.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\" />\n\n==Epidemiology==\nIn most studies, a majority of cell phone users report experiencing occasional phantom vibrations or ringing, with reported rates ranging from 27.4% to 89%.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Once every two weeks is a typical frequency for the sensations, though a minority experience them daily.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Some individuals may be seriously bothered by the sensations.<ref name=\"deb2014\" />\n\n==Management==\nLittle research has been done on treatment for phantom vibrations.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Carrying the cell phone in a different position reduces phantom vibrations for some people.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Other methods include turning off the vibration, changing the ringtone or vibration tone, or using a different device altogether.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2007-06-12-cellphones_N.htm |title=Good vibrations? Bad? None at all? |first=Angela |last=Haupt |work=[[USA Today]] |date=June 12, 2007 |publisher=[[Gannett Company|Gannett]] |location=[[McLean, VA]] |issn=0734-7456 |accessdate=September 4, 2011}}\n\n{{Mobile phones}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile phone culture]]\n[[Category:Technology neologisms]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Unsolved problems in neuroscience]]\n", "text_old": "'''Phantom vibration syndrome''' or '''phantom ringing syndrome''' is the perception that one's [[mobile phone]] is [[Vibrating alert|vibrating]] or ringing when it is not. Other terms for this concept include '''ringxiety''' (a [[portmanteau]] of ''[[ringtone|ring]]'' and ''[[anxiety]]''), '''fauxcellarm''' (a [[portmanteau]] of \"[[wikt:faux|faux]]\" /fo\u035c\u028a/ meaning \"[[wikt:fake|fake]]\" or \"[[wikt:false|false]]\" and \"[[cellphone]]\" and \"[[alarm]]\" pronounced similarly to \"[[false alarm]]\") and '''phonetom''' (a [[portmanteau]] of ''phone'' and ''phantom'').<ref name=\"Goodman\">{{cite news|last=Goodman|first=Brenda|title=I Hear Ringing and There's No One There. I Wonder Why.|work=The New York Times|page=1|date=4 May 2006|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/04/fashion/thursdaystyles/04phan.html}}</ref> According to Dr. Michael Rothberg, the term is not a syndrome, but is better characterised as a tactile hallucination since the brain perceives a sensation that is not actually present.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title = Phantom vibration syndrome among medical staff: a cross sectional survey|journal = BMJ|pages = c6914|volume = 341|issue = dec15 2|doi = 10.1136/bmj.c6914|pmid = 21159761|first = M. B.|last = Rothberg|first2 = A.|last2 = Arora|first3 = J.|last3 = Hermann|first4 = R.|last4 = Kleppel|first5 = P. S.|last5 = Marie|first6 = P.|last6 = Visintainer|year = 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"PhonetomFischer\">{{cite web | url= https://www.facebook.com/elli.fischer/posts/10106394546200008| title= Phonetom Definition| publisher= Facebook| date= October 3, 2017 | accessdate= October 3, 2017| quote=Phonetom: When you could swear you felt your phone vibrate, but it's not in your pocket.| author=  Fischer, Elli}}</ref> WebMD published an article on phantom vibration syndrome with Rothberg as a source. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/news/20160111/phones-phantom-vibration|title=Do You Have 'Phantom Vibration Syndrome'?|last=Locke|first=Tim|website=WebMD|language=en|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> Several other articles have been published in 2010s, including in NPR, Bustle, CBS News, and Psychology Today. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2013/09/30/226820044/phantom-phone-vibrations-so-common-they-ve-changed-our-brains|title=Phantom Phone Vibrations: So Common They've Changed Our Brains?|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/what-is-phantom-ringing-syndrome-youve-almost-certainly-experienced-it-before-15539483|title=Phantom Ringing Syndrome Is The Weird AF Condition You've Had But Never Heard Of|last=Hills|first=Megan C.|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/phantom-vibration-syndrome-common-in-cellphone-users/|title=\"Phantom vibration syndrome\" common in cellphone users|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/rewired-the-psychology-technology/201305/phantom-pocket-vibration-syndrome|title=Phantom Pocket Vibration Syndrome|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n\nPhantom ringing may be experienced while taking a shower, watching television, or using a noisy device. Humans are particularly sensitive to auditory tones between 1,000 and 6,000 [[hertz]], and basic mobile phone ringtones often fall within this range.<ref name=\"Goodman\"/> Phantom vibrations develop after carrying a cell phone set to use [[vibrating alert]]s.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Researcher [[Michelle Drouin]] found that almost 9 of 10 undergraduates at her college experienced phantom vibrations.<ref name=\"twsPsychologyToday\">{{cite web | url= http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/rewired-the-psychology-technology/201305/phantom-pocket-vibration-syndrome| title= Phantom Pocket Vibration Syndrome| publisher= Psychology Today| date= May 7, 2013 | accessdate= September 10, 2014| quote=...According to Dr. Michelle Drouin... 89% of the undergraduates in her study had experienced these phantom vibrations...| author=  Rosen, Larry}}</ref>{{mcn|date=November 2017}}\n\n==History==\nIn the comic strip ''[[Dilbert]]'', cartoonist [[Scott Adams]] referenced such a sensation in 1996 as \"phantom-pager syndrome\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dilbert.com/strips/comic/1996-09-16/ |title=Dilbert |last=Adams |first=Scott |date=September 16, 1996 |accessdate=October 16, 2013}}</ref> The earliest published use of the term ''phantom vibration syndrome'' dates to 2003 in an article entitled \"Phantom Vibration Syndrome\" published in the ''[[New Pittsburgh Courier]]'', written under a pen name of columnist Robert D. Jones. However, it is debated whether earlier noting of the onsets of PVS came from Michael J Lewis of Melbourne, Australia. In the conclusion of the article, Jones wrote, \"...should we be concerned about what our mind or body may be trying to tell us by the aggravating imaginary emanations from belts, pockets and even purses? Whether PVS is the result of physical nerve damage, a mental health issue, or both, this growing phenomenon seems to indicate that we may have crossed a line in this 'always on' society.\"\n\nThe first study of the phenomenon was conducted in 2007 by a researcher who coined the term ''ringxiety'' to describe it.<ref name=\"deb2014\">{{cite journal |authors=Deb A |title=Phantom vibration and phantom ringing among mobile phone users: A systematic review of literature |journal=Asia Pac Psychiatry |volume= 7|issue= 3|pages= 231\u20139|year=2014 |pmid=25408384 |doi=10.1111/appy.12164}}</ref> In 2012, the term ''phantom vibration syndrome'' was chosen as the Australian ''[[Macquarie Dictionary]]''{{'}}s word of the year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.crikey.com.au/fullysic/2013/02/07/phantom-vibration-syndrome-word-of-the-year/ |title=Phantom vibration syndrome: Word of the Year |last=Wilson |first=Aidan |work=Crikey.com.au |date=February 7, 2013 |accessdate=October 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.macquariedictionary.com.au/resources/view/word/of/the/year/|title = Macquarie Dictionary word of the year archives|last = Meacham|first = Merle|accessdate = March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\nThe cause of phantom vibrations is not known.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Preliminary research suggests it is related to over-involvement with one's cell phone.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Vibrations typically begin occurring after carrying a phone for between one month and one year.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> It has been suggested that, when anticipating a phone call, the [[cerebral cortex]] may misinterpret other sensory input (such as [[muscle contractions]], pressure from clothing, or music) as a phone vibration or ring tone.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> This may be understood as a human signal detection issue, with potentially significant influences from psychological attributes.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\"> Kruger, D. J., & Djerf, J. M. (2016). High Ringxiety: Attachment Anxiety Predicts Experiences of Phantom Cell Phone Ringing. Cyberpsychology, Behavior & Social Networking, 19(1), 56-59. </ref> Factors such as experiences, expectations, and psychological states influence the threshold for signal detection.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\" /> Some phantom vibration experiences may be a type of [[pareidolia]] and can therefore be examined as a psychological phenomenon influenced by individual variances in personality, condition, and context.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\" /> Attachment anxiety can also be seen as a predictor for the frequency of phantom vibration experiences since it is associated with psychological attributes related to insecurity in interpersonal relationships.<ref name=\"Kruger2016\" />\n\n==Epidemiology==\nIn most studies, a majority of cell phone users report experiencing occasional phantom vibrations or ringing, with reported rates ranging from 27.4% to 89%.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Once every two weeks is a typical frequency for the sensations, though a minority experience them daily.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Some individuals may be seriously bothered by the sensations.<ref name=\"deb2014\" />\n\n==Management==\nLittle research has been done on treatment for phantom vibrations.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Carrying the cell phone in a different position reduces phantom vibrations for some people.<ref name=\"deb2014\" /> Other methods include turning off the vibration, changing the ringtone or vibration tone, or using a different device altogether.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2007-06-12-cellphones_N.htm |title=Good vibrations? Bad? None at all? |first=Angela |last=Haupt |work=[[USA Today]] |date=June 12, 2007 |publisher=[[Gannett Company|Gannett]] |location=[[McLean, VA]] |issn=0734-7456 |accessdate=September 4, 2011}}\n\n{{Mobile phones}}\n\n[[Category:Mobile phone culture]]\n[[Category:Technology neologisms]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Unsolved problems in neuroscience]]\n", "name_user": "116.71.5.35", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phantom_vibration_syndrome"}
{"title_page": "Edmund Marshall", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Dr Edmund Marshall\n|image =\n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Goole]]\n|term_start = 27 May 1971\n|term_end = 9 June 1983\n|predecessor = [[George Jeger]]\n|successor = ''Constituency abolished''\n|birth_name = Edmund Ian Marshall\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|05|31|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n|nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place =\n|spouse =  \n|party = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (since 1988)<br />[[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] (1985\u20131988)<br />[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1967\u20131985)<br />[[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] (before 1967)\n|alma_mater = [[Magdalen College, Oxford]]<br />[[University of Liverpool]]\n}}\n'''Edmund Ian Marshall''' (born 31 May 1940 in [[Manchester]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]] and churchman.\n\n==Early life==\nMarshall was educated at Humberstone Foundation School (also known as [[Clee Grammar School for Boys]] for Boys and became the comprehensive [[Matthew Humberstone School]] in September 1973) on ''Clee Road'' in [[Old Clee]], [[Cleethorpes]], and [[Magdalen College, Oxford]], where he took double first class honours in mathematics and was awarded a University Junior Mathematical Prize in 1961. He gained a PhD from the [[University of Liverpool]] in 1965. He became a mathematics university lecturer and a [[Methodist]] local preacher. He served as Vice-president of the Methodist Conference in 1992.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nMarshall was a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] councillor on [[Wallasey Borough Council]] 1963-65 and parliamentary candidate for [[Louth, Lincolnshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Louth]] in [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]] and [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966]], but joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1967.\n\nIn a [[1971 Goole by-election|1971 by-election]], Marshall was elected as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Goole]]. From 1976\u20139, he served as Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Home Secretary, and as Chair of the Select Committee on Trade and Industry.  He left Parliament in 1983, when the Goole constituency was abolished in boundary changes.\n\n==After Parliament==\nIn 1985 Marshall transferred to the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] and subsequently became a member of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. He fought [[Bridlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridlington]] for the SDP in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]], coming second. In 2015 he became a Trustee of the Parliamentary Outreach Trust.\n\nFrom 1997 to 2007 he advised the [[Church of England]] [[Bishop of Wakefield (diocese)|Bishop of Wakefield]] on [[ecumenical]] matters, and from 2000 to 2015 was a member of the General Synod of the Church of England.\n\nMarshall is the author of two published books:  Parliament and the Public (Macmillan 1982) and Business and Society (Routledge 1993).\n\nFrom 1984\u20132000, he was a lecturer in [http://www.brad.ac.uk/acad/management/external/ Management Science] at the [[University of Bradford School of Management]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1969 he married Margaret Pamela Antill in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]]. They have a daughter (born 1975).\nIn 2019 he married Margaret Anthea Masding (n\u00e9e [[Priestfield House|Martin Smith]]) in [[Magdalen College of Oxford University|Oxford]].\n\n== References ==\n*''Times Guide to the House of Commons'', 1966 & 1979\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060618215300/http://www.yhld.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/ Yorkshire and the Humber Liberals Democrats website]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/edmund_marshall/goole They Work For You]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[George Jeger]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Goole]]\n  | years  = [[1971 Goole by-election|1971]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = ''Constituency abolished'' }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marshall, Edmund}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:People from Cleethorpes]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Merseyside]]\n[[Category:English Methodists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Dr Edmund Marshall\n|image =\n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Goole]]\n|term_start = 27 May 1971\n|term_end = 9 June 1983\n|predecessor = [[George Jeger]]\n|successor = ''Constituency abolished''\n|birth_name = Edmund Ian Marshall\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|05|31|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n|nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|death_date = \n|death_place =\n|spouse =  \n|party = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (since 1988)<br />[[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] (1985\u20131988)<br />[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1967\u20131985)<br />[[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] (before 1967)\n|alma_mater = [[Magdalen College, Oxford]]<br />[[University of Liverpool]]\n}}\n'''Edmund Ian Marshall''' (born 31 May 1940 in [[Manchester]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]] and churchman.\n\n==Early life==\nMarshall was educated at Humberstone Foundation School (also known as [[Clee Grammar School for Boys]] for Boys and became the comprehensive [[Matthew Humberstone School]] in September 1973) on ''Clee Road'' in [[Old Clee]], [[Cleethorpes]], and [[Magdalen College, Oxford]], where he took double first class honours in mathematics and was awarded a University Junior Mathematical Prize in 1961. He gained a PhD from the [[University of Liverpool]] in 1965. He became a mathematics university lecturer and a [[Methodist]] local preacher. He served as Vice-president of the Methodist Conference in 1992.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nMarshall was a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] councillor on [[Wallasey Borough Council]] 1963-65 and parliamentary candidate for [[Louth, Lincolnshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Louth]] in [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]] and [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966]], but joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1967.\n\nIn a [[1971 Goole by-election|1971 by-election]], Marshall was elected as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Goole]]. From 1976-9, he served as Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Home Secretary, and as Chair of the Select Committee on Trade and Industry.  He left Parliament in 1983, when the Goole constituency was abolished in boundary changes.\n\n==After Parliament==\nIn 1985 Marshall transferred to the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] and subsequently became a member of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. He fought [[Bridlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridlington]] for the SDP in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]], coming second. In 2015 he became a Trustee of the Parliamentary Outreach Trust.\n\nFrom 1997 to 2007 he advised the [[Church of England]] [[Bishop of Wakefield (diocese)|Bishop of Wakefield]] on [[ecumenical]] matters, and from 2000 to 2015 was a member of the General Synod of the Church of England.\n\nMarshall is the author of two published books:  Parliament and the Public (Macmillan 1982) and Business and Society (Routledge 1993).\n\nFrom 1984-2000, he was a lecturer in [http://www.brad.ac.uk/acad/management/external/ Management Science] at the [[University of Bradford School of Management]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1969 he married Margaret Pamela Antill in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]]. They have a daughter (born 1975).\nIn 2019 he married Margaret Anthea Masding (n\u00e9e [[Priestfield House|Martin Smith]]) in [[Magdalen College of Oxford University|Oxford]].\n\n== References ==\n*''Times Guide to the House of Commons'', 1966 & 1979\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060618215300/http://www.yhld.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/ Yorkshire and the Humber Liberals Democrats website]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/edmund_marshall/goole They Work For You]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[George Jeger]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Goole]]\n  | years  = [[1971 Goole by-election|1971]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = ''Constituency abolished'' }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marshall, Edmund}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK M