{"title_page": "James Lamond", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n'''James Alexander Lamond''' (29 November 1928 \u2013 20 November 2007) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] who represented [[Oldham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East]] from 1970 to 1983 and then [[Oldham West and Royton (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham Central and Royton]] from [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] until he retired at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nLamond was born in [[Burrelton]], [[Perthshire]].  His father worked for the [[London and North Eastern Railway]].  He was educated at schools in Burrelton and [[Coupar Angus]], before becoming an [[apprentice]] [[technical drawing|draughtsman]] at the Hall and Company shipyard in Aberdeen in 1942, aged 14.  He could not afford the fees to study [[naval architecture]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], and worked as a draughtsman for the North-east Scotland Regional Hospital Board.\n\nHe was an active member of the Draughtsmen's and Allied Technicians' Association (Data; later successively renamed as [[Amalgamated Union of Engineering Workers|AUEW]]-[[Technical, Administrative and Supervisory Section|Tass]], [[Manufacturing, Science and Finance|MSF]], [[Amicus (trade union)|Amicus]] and [[Unite (trade union)|Unite]]).  He joined the Labour party in 1950, and was elected to [[Aberdeen City Council]] in 1959, serving as a councillor until 1971.  He became leader of the local Labour group in 1967, and served as [[Lord Provost]] and [[Lord Lieutenant]] of Aberdeen in 1970\u201371.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45134|page=6953|date=23 June 1970}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45383|page=5890|date=4 June 1971}}</ref>  After he failed to be selected for the safe Labour seat of [[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]], losing out to [[Robert Hughes, Baron Hughes of Woodside|Robert Hughes]], he found favour instead in [[Oldham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East]], where he was elected in June 1970.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45134|page=6946|date=23 June 1970}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46229|page=2988|date=7 March 1974}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46374|page=8987|date=15 October 1974}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47838|page=6055|date=10 May 1979}}</ref>\n\nHe was on the left-wing of the Labour party, alongside [[Tony Benn]] and [[Eric Heffer]]. He opposed the plans for [[devolution]] in [[Scotland]], voting against the Scotland Bill in 1977. Also in 1977, he was upbraided by the Speaker after making some forthright remarks about [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]].  Lamond supported Tony Benn in his unsuccessful bid to become the Labour party's deputy leader in 1980.\n\nHe was a vice-president of the [[World Peace Council]], president of the British Peace Assembly, founder chairman of the British-East German Society. In the 1980s, he was criticised as an apologist of the Communist regime in the Soviet Union, particularly after he provided justifications for the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\">{{cite news|last=Roth|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew Roth|title=James Lamond: Leftwing MP whose penchant for peace was seen as pro-Soviet|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/dec/21/labour.uk|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 December 2007|accessdate=13 February 2008|quote=an apologist for the USSR's failed attempt to take over Afghanistan in 1979.}}</ref>  In a debate in the House of Commons in July 1980, the World Peace Council was criticised by Conservative Foreign Office minister [[Peter Blaker]] as a \"disguised instrument of Soviet policy\", a charge that Lamond rejected (although he later accepted that much of its funding did indeed come from the Soviet Union).\n\nAfter constituency boundaries were redrawn for the 1983 election, he moved to the new seat of [[Oldham West and Royton (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham Central and Royton]], selected ahead of [[Joel Barnett, Baron Barnett|Joel Barnett]]. He opposed the location of US [[cruise missile]]s and [[Pershing missile]]s in the UK in December 1983.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49394|page=8203|date=21 June 1983}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=50974|page=8001|date=23 June 1987}}</ref> He supported the declining textile industry in his  constituency. He served on the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] from 1975 to 1983, and served on the Speaker's panel from 1979 until he retired at the 1992 general election.\n\n== Local politics again ==\n\nLamond returned to local politics after leaving Parliament, serving as a member of [[Grampian Regional Council]] from 1994 to 1996. He became a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of Aberdeen in 1995.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54155|page=12381|date=12 September 1995}}</ref>  He rejoined Aberdeen City Council in 1995, serving alongside his wife, before both retired in May 2007.<ref>[http://www.thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=149235&command=displayContent&sourceNode=149218&contentPK=19026448&moduleName=InternalSearch&formname=sidebarsearch North of Scotland - Aberdeen News - Press and Journal<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305202005/http://thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/displaynode.jsp?command=displaycontent&contentpk=19026448&formname=sidebarsearch&modulename=internalsearch&nodeid=149235&sourcenode=149218 |date=5 March 2016}}</ref> He was chairman of the Royal Aberdeen Workshops for the Blind and Disabled from 2002 to 2004.\n\nWith his wife June Wellburn in 1954, Lamond had three daughters, all of whom survived him. He suffered from pneumonia in later life.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/james-lamond-mp-of-unswerving-convictions-764098.html Obituary in ''The Independent'', 10 December 2007]\n* [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article3030573.ece Obituary in ''The Times'', 11 December 2007]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/12/11/db1103.xml Obituary in ''The Daily Telegraph'', 11 December 2007]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,,2230741,00.html Obituary in ''The Guardian'', 21 December 2007]\n*''The [[Times Guide to the House of Commons]]'', [[The Times|Times Newspapers Ltd]], 1987\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-lamond | James Lamond }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Charles Mapp]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oldham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East]]\n  | years  = [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oldham Central and Royton (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham Central and Royton]]\n  | years  = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Bryan Davies, Baron Davies of Oldham|Bryan Davies]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamond, James}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Technical, Administrative and Supervisory Section-sponsored MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]]\n[[Category:Lord Provosts of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:People from Perthshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n'''James Alexander Lamond''' (29 November 1928 \u2013 20 November 2007) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] who represented [[Oldham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East]] from 1970 to 1983 and then [[Oldham West and Royton (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham Central and Royton]] from [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] until he retired at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nLamond was born in [[Burrelton]], [[Perthshire]].  His father worked for the [[London and North Eastern Railway]].  He was educated at schools in Burrelton and [[Coupar Angus]], before becoming an [[apprentice]] [[technical drawing|draughtsman]] at the Hall and Company shipyard in Aberdeen in 1942, aged 14.  He could not afford the fees to study [[naval architecture]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], and worked as a draughtsman for the North-east Scotland Regional Hospital Board.\n\nHe was an active member of the Draughtsmen's and Allied Technicians' Association (Data; later successively renamed as [[Amalgamated Union of Engineering Workers|AUEW]]-[[Technical, Administrative and Supervisory Section|Tass]], [[Manufacturing, Science and Finance|MSF]], [[Amicus (trade union)|Amicus]] and [[Unite (trade union)|Unite]]).  He joined the Labour party in 1950, and was elected to [[Aberdeen City Council]] in 1959, serving as a councillor until 1971.  He became leader of the local Labour group in 1967, and served as [[Lord Provost]] and [[Lord Lieutenant]] of Aberdeen in 1970-71.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45134|page=6953|date=23 June 1970}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45383|page=5890|date=4 June 1971}}</ref>  After he failed to be selected for the safe Labour seat of [[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]], losing out to [[Robert Hughes, Baron Hughes of Woodside|Robert Hughes]], he found favour instead in [[Oldham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East]], where he was elected in June 1970.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45134|page=6946|date=23 June 1970}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46229|page=2988|date=7 March 1974}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46374|page=8987|date=15 October 1974}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47838|page=6055|date=10 May 1979}}</ref>\n\nHe was on the left-wing of the Labour party, alongside [[Tony Benn]] and [[Eric Heffer]]. He opposed the plans for [[devolution]] in [[Scotland]], voting against the Scotland Bill in 1977. Also in 1977, he was upbraided by the Speaker after making some forthright remarks about [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]].  Lamond supported Tony Benn in his unsuccessful bid to become the Labour party's deputy leader in 1980.\n\nHe was a vice-president of the [[World Peace Council]], president of the British Peace Assembly, founder chairman of the British-East German Society. In the 1980s, he was criticised as an apologist of the Communist regime in the Soviet Union, particularly after he provided justifications for the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\">{{cite news|last=Roth|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew Roth|title=James Lamond: Leftwing MP whose penchant for peace was seen as pro-Soviet|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/dec/21/labour.uk|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 December 2007|accessdate=13 February 2008|quote=an apologist for the USSR's failed attempt to take over Afghanistan in 1979.}}</ref>  In a debate in the House of Commons in July 1980, the World Peace Council was criticised by Conservative Foreign Office minister [[Peter Blaker]] as a \"disguised instrument of Soviet policy\", a charge that Lamond rejected (although he later accepted that much of its funding did indeed come from the Soviet Union).\n\nAfter constituency boundaries were redrawn for the 1983 election, he moved to the new seat of [[Oldham West and Royton (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham Central and Royton]], selected ahead of [[Joel Barnett, Baron Barnett|Joel Barnett]]. He opposed the location of US [[cruise missile]]s and [[Pershing missile]]s in the UK in December 1983.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49394|page=8203|date=21 June 1983}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=50974|page=8001|date=23 June 1987}}</ref> He supported the declining textile industry in his  constituency. He served on the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] from 1975 to 1983, and served on the Speaker's panel from 1979 until he retired at the 1992 general election.\n\n== Local politics again ==\n\nLamond returned to local politics after leaving Parliament, serving as a member of [[Grampian Regional Council]] from 1994 to 1996. He became a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of Aberdeen in 1995.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54155|page=12381|date=12 September 1995}}</ref>  He rejoined Aberdeen City Council in 1995, serving alongside his wife, before both retired in May 2007.<ref>[http://www.thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=149235&command=displayContent&sourceNode=149218&contentPK=19026448&moduleName=InternalSearch&formname=sidebarsearch North of Scotland - Aberdeen News - Press and Journal<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305202005/http://thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/displaynode.jsp?command=displaycontent&contentpk=19026448&formname=sidebarsearch&modulename=internalsearch&nodeid=149235&sourcenode=149218 |date=5 March 2016}}</ref> He was chairman of the Royal Aberdeen Workshops for the Blind and Disabled from 2002 to 2004.\n\nWith his wife June Wellburn in 1954, Lamond had three daughters, all of whom survived him. He suffered from pneumonia in later life.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/james-lamond-mp-of-unswerving-convictions-764098.html Obituary in ''The Independent'', 10 December 2007]\n* [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article3030573.ece Obituary in ''The Times'', 11 December 2007]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/12/11/db1103.xml Obituary in ''The Daily Telegraph'', 11 December 2007]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/obituaries/story/0,,2230741,00.html Obituary in ''The Guardian'', 21 December 2007]\n*''The [[Times Guide to the House of Commons]]'', [[The Times|Times Newspapers Ltd]], 1987\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-lamond | James Lamond }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Charles Mapp]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oldham East (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East]]\n  | years  = [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Oldham Central and Royton (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham Central and Royton]]\n  | years  = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Bryan Davies, Baron Davies of Oldham|Bryan Davies]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamond, James}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Technical, Administrative and Supervisory Section-sponsored MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]]\n[[Category:Lord Provosts of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:People from Perthshire]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1970-71 \u2192 1970\u201371", "url